<HEADLINE> Masood Refuses to Talk with Taliban Individually </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's former
military chief Ahmad Masood today ruled out the possibility of
holding talks individually with the Islamic Taliban militia,
Taliban sources said.
</P>
<P>
"I will not talk with Taliban individually," Masood was quoted
as saying by Taliban sources in Peshawar, a major city in
northwestern Pakistan, according to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
"If the Taliban are really interested in resolving the current
crisis, they should hold dialogue with all the parties in the
northern alliance," said the Tajik warlord, who was routed out of
the Afghan capital Kabul by the Taliban 11 months ago.
</P>
<P>
Masood is one of the strongmen in the anti-Taliban northern
alliance which is composed mainly of forces led by Masood, Uzbek
warlord Abdul Malik and Shiite Hezb-e-Wadhat leader Karim Khalili.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban sources also disclosed that the chief of the
militia's Supreme Council, Muhammad Rabbani, has left Kabul for
Saudi Arabia for medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani, who is accompanied by five senior Taliban officials,
will discuss matters of mutual interest with leaders of Saudi
Arabia, which has already recognized the Taliban government, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Sporadic fighting has been continuing north of Kabul for nearly
two months after a surprise attack by Masood brought his forces to
within the rocket range of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
But since the late July advance, neither side has been able to
deal a decisive blow at the front, which zigzags through the
fertile Shamali Valley that sweeps north from Kabul to the snowy
Hindu Kush mountains.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
