<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Warns PNA Against Failure of American </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu today warned against the failure of American
peace efforts if the Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
continues refusing to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the pending visit to the region by United
States Secretary of State Madeleine Albright next week,
Netanyahu told Israel Radio that the American peace efforts
would not go far as long as PNA leader Yasser Arafat
refused to carry out his promises to combat terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"Secretary Albright had the right when she put the primacy
of security in the peace process. If the Palestinian Authority
continues to refuse to fight the infrastructure of terror
organizations, our peace efforts would not go very far.
Indeed, I would say, the entire peace process would be in
danger," he said.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu blasted Arafat and Palestinian security chief in
the West Bank Jibril Rajoub for embracing leaders of the
militant Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas) recently during the
two-day "national unity conference."
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that the PNA had yet followed through
the list of 150 suspected Palestinian terrorists handed over
by Israel, and refused to taken actions against the militant
groups and their infrastructure, and the incitement of violence
against Israel.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu stressed that "no engagement" with Hamas and any
other terror organizations was justified, because the goal of
these groups is to destroy Israel.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's remarks indicated his intransigency on the stance
on security despite of the pending visit by Albright, who is
to try to revive the deeply-troubled Israeli-Palestinian peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Albright is due to arrive in the region on September 10
for her first Middle East peace mission seven months after
assuming office, during which she will visit Israel, Palestine,
Syria, Egypt, Jordan and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
In order to prepare for Albright's visit, a high-level
Israeli delegation led by Cabinet Secretary Danny Naveh will
depart for Washington Tuesday night. The delegation included
Netanyahu's diplomatic adviser Uzi Arad, his attorney Yitzhak
Molcho and senior officials from the Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Since the July 30 Hamas-claimed twin suicide bombings in
Jerusalem which have killed 17 people, Israel has been
pressuring the PNA to crack down on Hamas and other militant
groups.
</P>
<P>
During Albright's visit here, Israel is expected to
request her to push Arafat hard on the issue of fighting
terrorism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
