<HEADLINE> SADC Leaders to Hold Annual Summit in Malawi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) will hold their annual
summit in Malawi next week to discuss regional economic
development and security situation.
</P>
<P>
South African president Nelson Mandela, who assumed SADC's
three- year chairmanship last year, will chair the summit,a
foreign ministry statement issued today in Pretoria said.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the summit is to discuss general progress in the
community, and to establish strategic positions on the future
direction of the regional body in order to promote regional
integration in southern Africa, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Items on the agenda include a declaration on gender equality
and a proposed process of review and rationalisation of the SADC
program of action.
</P>
<P>
Protocols on education, training and mining would be
considered for adoption and a declaration on productivity in SADC
would be made, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The issue of the ban on the use, production and distribution
of land- mines will also be deliberated.
</P>
<P>
South African foreign minister Alfred Nzo will chair a two-day
SADC council of ministers meeting leading up to the summit on
September 8.
</P>
<P>
A committee of senior officials began a two-day meeting in
Blantyre yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Situation in Angola and lifting of sanctions against Burundi
will also be disccussed by the summit.
</P>
<P>
SADC was formed five years ago to coordinate efforts for a
common market. The regional grouping is made up by 12 countries,
with a total population of 150 million and a combined gross
domestic product of 170 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
