<HEADLINE> Singapore to Further Improve Syllabus for Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Singapore will further
improve the syllabus and the text books for Chinese language
education so as to focus more on conveying cultural values and
heritage, Deputy Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong said today as he
launched this year's Speak Mandarin Campaign.
</P>
<P>
"We should ensure that the higher Chinese and also the Chinese
syllabi and textbooks convey Chinese cultural values and heritage,
and do not just teach the language for utilitarian purposes," the
deputy prime minister stressed.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Education will do this progressively over the
next few years, he said. But he added that in doing this, it
should be careful not to make the subject more difficult.
</P>
<P>
Making higher Chinese harder will reduce the number of pupils
who can cope with the subject, he warned. "This will defeat our
purpose."
</P>
<P>
He noted that only about 10 to 20 percent of the students take
higher Chinese at the primary and secondary schools and at junior
colleges in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
A sound approach to teaching Chinese in schools will lay the
foundation for wider use of Chinese in the Singapore society, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"We must take a flexible and pragmatic approach towards
teaching, learning and promoting Chinese, in order to reach all
segments of society," he added.
</P>
<P>
By catering to the varied needs, "we give the Chinese language
the best chance of flourishing in Singapore," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
