<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC States Set for Crucial Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The member countries of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) will meet in a
crucial 17th annual summit in Malawi this week during which they
will review the organisation's structures, consider enlargement,
resolve the thorny issues of trade as well as a number of
protocols meant to consolidate economic integration.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe News Agency reported today that the summit kicks
off with a two-day council of ministers meeting starting on
Wednesday which will set the agenda for the heads of state and
government meeting which starts on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe will be represented by foreign affairs minister Stan
Mudenge while president Robert Mugabe is expected to join other
leaders on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The summit is the first after last year's historical Maseru
summit which culminated in the signing of four key protocols as
the grouping moved closer to creating a free trade zone.
</P>
<P>
The four protocols signed last year were on trade, transport,
communication and meteorology, energy and combating trafficking
in illicit drugs.
</P>
<P>
The trade protocol, which is yet to be ratified by 10 of the
12 member states, seeks, among other things, to eradicate tariff
barriers in the region over a period of eight years.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, the regional powerhouse, is reportedly
finalising its offer to the other member states under which it
hopes to reduce tariffs on trade to zero, except in sensitive
sectors like those involved in vulnerable production.
</P>
<P>
Items on this year's agenda include a declaration on gender
equality and proposal to review and rationalise the SADC
programme of action in light of the reports of lack of funds for
various sectoral projects.
</P>
<P>
Protocols on education, training and mining would be
considered for adoption and a declaration on productivity in SADC
is expected to be made.
</P>
<P>
The summit is also expected to consider applications by the
Democratic Republic of Congo, Kenya, Uganda and Seychelles to
join the regional grouping which currently has a combined
population of approximately 128 million people.
</P>
<P>
SADC has also been reviewing its structures following its
transformation from the anti-apartheid Southern African
Development Co-ordination Conference to the Southern African
Development Community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
