<HEADLINE> US Federal Minimum Wage Increases This Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. federal minimum
wage was increased by 40 cents an hour to 5.15 dollars from
September 1 as part of the second phrase of an increase package
approved by the U.S. Congress last year.
</P>
<P>
The first phrase last fall lifted the nation's standard wage
for hourly workers to 4.75 dollars from 4.25 dollars, where it had
sat unchanged for more than five years.
</P>
<P>
The change will affect more people than just the estimated 6.4
million workers who now make below 5.15 dollars per hour. Overall,
about 10 million minimum-wage workers will have benefited from the
increase, The Wall Street Journal reported today.
</P>
<P>
More than 90 percent of the Americans receiving the minimum
wage work in private-sector jobs such as retail stores and
restaurants, sales or private household jobs like housekeepers.
</P>
<P>
Of those getting the minimum wage increase, roughly 57 percent
are women, 32 percent are youths ages 16 to 19, and 55 percent
work part time, according to the statistics from the U.S. Labor
Department. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
