<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Camerounian MPs Split over Bill on Presidential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, September 2 (Xinhua) --After four days of scrutiny of
the bill on presidential election tabled at the National Assembly
of Cameroun, parliamentarians appeared more divided in opinion
now than they started, Cameroun Tribune reported today.
</P>
<P>
The deadlock was imminent when parliamentarians of the
Constitutional Laws Committee agreed to analyse and open debates
on the bill Monday.
</P>
<P>
So far, three articles have caused major debate: one which
empowers the Ministry of Territorial Administration to receive,
examine and maybe reject application files of candidates, was
severely criticised by most of the opposition party members of
the committee. They prefer that such powers be conferred on the
constitutional council.
</P>
<P>
Another issue which is yet to be resolved is the building up
of the divisional supervisory commission which most of the
opposition parliamentarians consider too representative of the
administration.
</P>
<P>
Most parliamentarians prefer to see more representatives from
the independent group replace some of the local administrative
officials in the various commissions.
</P>
<P>
By midday Monday, the committee is still in session and there
was little or no signs that the members would easily agree
through consensus on all the articles.
</P>
<P>
However, parliamentarians of the ruling Cameroun People's
Democratic Movement which has an overwhelming majority in the
committee may break the deadlock by taking a common stance if the
need arises. For now, it is open debate.
</P>
<P>
The parliamentarians have been working for eight days since
the first extraordinary session of the parliament convened on
August 26.
</P>
<P>
During the eight days, the mandates of the seven
parliamentarians elected on August 3 in a re-run in three
electoral constituencies had been validated.
</P>
<P>
As soon as the present debates on the bill are through, it
will take on the bill related to private security companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
