<HEADLINE> First Palestinian Political Meeting Ends In Gaza </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The first political meeting
of Palestinian national and Islamic factions concluded in Gaza
today, reported the East Jerusalem-based Palestinian press service
JMCC (Jerusalem Media and Communication Center).
</P>
<P>
Thiab Al-Louh, member of the Revolutionary Council of
Palestinina leader Yasser Arafat's Fatah movement who attended in
the three-day conference, said that the participants discussed
political issues and ways of confronting challenges.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also focused on relations between the national and
Islamic factions and the Palestinian National Authority, and
issues of international affairs concerning the establishment of a
democratic civil society, he said.
</P>
<P>
"All participants agreed upon confronting aggressive measures
of occupation and the policies of closure, siege, political
blackmail (by Israel), in disregard of Palestine's dignity," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Concerning the issue of Palestinian refugees, he said the
participants asked the United Nations Relief Works Agency (UNRWA)
to provide more services to the refugees instead of reducing
financial support.
</P>
<P>
UNRWA is now serving 3.4 million Palestinian refugees. Two
million of those are scattered in camps throughout Lebanon, Syria
and Jordan. The remainder live in Palestine.
</P>
<P>
According to UNRWA, it received so far no more than 207
million U.S. dollars towards its projected budget of 312 million
dollars for 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
