<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africans Warned of Nigerian Fraud Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 2 (Xinhua) -- South Africans have been
warned not to fall prey to a Nigerian fraud network currently
operating in the country.
</P>
<P>
The National Detective Branch said in a press release today
that the scheme, internationally known as 419, had emerged as one
of the most lucrative fraudulent activities perpetrated by
organised crime syndicates in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
South African police said criminals have now set up bases in
the country from where they send out frauding letters.
</P>
<P>
The writers usually claim to represent prominent political
officers or major corporations and say they are in South Africa
to buy arms for the war in the former Zaire.
</P>
<P>
People who receive such letters are urged not to be fooled by
documents, some of which carry the logo of the Federal Government
of Nigeria, the Central Bank of Nigeria or any other government
agency.
</P>
<P>
South African police warn people not to respond to such
letters for, giving out their bank details can result in loss of
money and valuables. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
