<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Appeals for Dialogue, Negotiations in Comoros </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 2 (Xinhua) -- France today appealed for
dialogue and negotiations in the Indian Ocean island nation of
Comoros after hundreds of Comoran soldiers were reportedly on
their way to the separatist island of Anjouan.
</P>
<P>
"The solution to the problems which the Federal Islamic
Republic of the Comoros now undergo cannot be found but in the
dialogue and negotiation between all the Comoran parties
concerned, in the respect of unity, cohesion and territorial
integrity (of the country)," said French Foreign Ministry
spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that France supports the efforts being made
by the Organization of African Unity (OAU) to arrange an
inter-Comoran peace conference in the Ethiopian capital Addis
Abeba on September 10-15, and invited all parties concerned to
cooperate with the OAU in a "constructive spirit."
</P>
<P>
He recalled that the OAU envoy to Comoros, Pierre Yere, is also
evaluating the needs for economic and humanitarian aid to the
local people.
</P>
<P>
The OAU envoy to said today that the Comoran government has
asked for a postponement of the Addis Abeba peace talks.
</P>
<P>
"We call on all parties concerned to facilitate the task of
these missions (by OAU) whose objective is to open the way for a
solution which is reached by consensus, lasting and pacific, to
the problems which is experienced by Comoros," said Rummelhardt.
</P>
<P>
The Comoran island of Anjouan declared "independence" in
early August and had asked for the return of French rule, which
was withdrawn from the Indian Ocean archipelago in 1975. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
