<HEADLINE> New Pest Detected in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 2 (Xinhua) -- An extremely serious
pest found in bees has been detected in South Africa for the
first time, the Southern African Broadcasting Association
reported today.
</P>
<P>
An official of the agricultural research council was quoted as
saying the parasite, known as varroa jacobsoni, is a considerable
threat to the bee-keeping industry in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Researchers said there is no total effective control for the
varroa mite and regular treatment of hives will be necessary.
</P>
<P>
They said chemicals registered in Europe and the United States
will have to be cleared for use in South Africa as an emergency
measure.
</P>
<P>
The use of commercial bees for crop pollination is a big
business in South Africa, valued at more than 400 million U.S.
dollars per year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
