<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC to Coordinate Position on Lome Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Member states of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) are expected to
table a final set of recommendations on future trade relations
with the European Union (EU) at their summit next week in Malawi.
</P>
<P>
SADC spokesman Kgosinkwe Moesi said today in Gaborone,
Botswana that SADC ministers have worked with other stakeholders
to establish a Southern African position on the review of the
Lome Convention.
</P>
<P>
Moesi was quoted by local media as saying that if approved by
the summit, the proposals will become SADC's contribution to the
African position on the Lome Convention.
</P>
<P>
The convention is a trade and aid arrangement bringing
together the 15 EU member states and 70 countries in Africa,
Caribbean and Pacific (ACP).
</P>
<P>
The accord is due for renewal at the turn of the century with
both sides scheduled to open negotiations on the convention next
year.
</P>
<P>
No official position exists within the SADC, but calls have
been made for trade concessions of the Lome Convention to be
restored in a post-1999 agreement.
</P>
<P>
The EU has mapped out a number of scenarios for future ACP-EU
cooperation, including breaking the ACP bloc into regions and
asking some countries to grant free market concessions to EU
exporters.
</P>
<P>
SADC was formed in 1992 to coordinate efforts for a common
market by 2000. The regional body is made up of 12 countries,
with a total population of 150 million and a combined gross
domestic product of 170 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian FM Meets with Zimbabwean President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom
Ikimi, special envoy for the country's leader Sani Abacha, today
delivered a special message to Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
at his office.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Mugabe, Ikimi told reporters that the
message centered on the annual ECOWAS (the Economic Community of
West Africa States) summit held in Abuja last Friday, during
which Abacha served as the chairman.
</P>
<P>
"We looked into the situation in Liberia and Sierra Leone,
among other issues of common interest," he said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister added that Abacha had also presided over
the recent installation of Liberian President Charles Taylor
following the successful implementation of the Abuja peace plan
on the west African country, which included a return to civilian
rule and disarmament.
</P>
<P>
The peace plan had resulted in elections which had been
declared as "free and fair" by the international community, and
an end to the civil war in Liberia, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Ikimi noted, some 11,000 ECOWAS troops would remain
in Liberia for six months after the elections in the interest of
and the need for, stability and security while the country
restructured its defense and police forces.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of Sierra Leone, Ikimi said the military coup
which took place as African leaders were holding the Organisation
of African Unity summit in Harare, had been condemned worldwide.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS took it upon itself to remedy the situation through a
committee of four countries consisting of Nigeria, Cote d'Ivoire,
Ghana and Guinea, which later met the coup leaders.
</P>
<P>
Ikimi said, ECOWAS imposed an economic blockade on Sierra
Leone and formally extended the mandate of its forces covering
the country.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the moves Nigeria had made in returning to
civilian rule and democracy, Ikimi said the process was onging
and October 1, 1998 was officially earmarked as the end of
military rule.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said he appreciated efforts ECOWAS was making to return
Liberia to civilian rule.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the people of Liberia would
appreciate those efforts which had cost a lot of resources to
both Nigeria and Liberia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
