<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Convention on Desertification Ratified in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's parliament today
finally ratified the U.N. convention to combat desertification in
countries experiencing serious drought, especially in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The convention, concluded in 1994 in Paris, is a product of
the U.N. Conference on Environment and Development which took
place in Rio de Janeiro in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Developing countries, identified as being at risk from drought
and desertification, are required to create an enabling
environment for implementing the convention.
</P>
<P>
Ratification of the convention also binds a country to drawing
up a national action program and give priority to drought and
desertification issues as well as creating a desertification
fund.
</P>
<P>
The parliamentarians said if conservation was to bear fruit,
especially in the rural areas, people should be provided with
alternative forms of fuel and energy.
</P>
<P>
Responding to concerns raised by the parliamentarians, Mines,
Environment and Tourism Minister Simon Moyo said, a
multi-sectoral task force had been established to work on
creating the fund and the national action program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
