<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Bans Reporting on Minister's Libel Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian prosecution
authority today banned the press from following up a libel lawsuit
filed by the interior minister against an opposition newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The ban would remain effective until the end of the
investigations, Ragaa Al-Arabi, Egyptian attorney general said in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
"The national, partisan, local and foreign press are not
allowed to publish reports of any more developments connected with
Interior Minister Hassan el-Alfy's libel charges against the
editor in chief and some reporters of the opposition newspaper
Al-Shaab," he said. But he did explain the reason.
</P>
<P>
For a month Al Shaab has been accusing el-Alfy and his
associates of racketeering, nepotism and involvement in a
high-profile corruption case.
</P>
<P>
Tensions between the Interior Ministry and the bi-weekly
mounted as el-Alfy filed a libel suit on August 16 against
Al-Shaab which then filed a counter lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
Since August 20, the attorney general's office has been
questioning the implicated journalists.
</P>
<P>
Magdy Hussein, editor in chief of the newspaper, said he
presented "100 pages of incriminating documents against el-Alfy
and his acolytes."
</P>
<P>
Hussein claimed he had proof that el-Alfy, who was supposed to
keep corruption under his vigilance, had sold a villa he bought
from the government to Abdel Wahab Habbak, a former public sector
company baron who is serving a 10-year imprisonment sentence for
corruption.
</P>
<P>
El-Alfy has in fact labeled Al-Shaab a tool of the outlawed
Muslim Brothers, implying the paper could get the same treatment
reserved for those Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
"Everything that is printed in this newspaper is a lie," he
told the press earlier.
</P>
<P>
El-Alfy's ministry is fighting a war against Islamic militants
that have staged a violent terrorist campaign since 1992 to
overthrow Egypt's incumbent secular government.
</P>
<P>
The case was the second prominent lawsuit in two months against
the press. President Hosni Mubarak' two sons last month brought a
Saudi paper to court for publishing a "defamatory" story of their
business dealings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
