<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank, IMF to Reduce Mozambique's Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) have proposed Mozambique be
granted debt relief worth 2.25 billion U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Southern African Broadcasting Association (SABA) reported
today from Maputo that the two institutions say this will help
reduce the burden of Mozambique's external borrowings to bearable
levels.
</P>
<P>
The assistance program will be the largest considered so far
under the highly-indebted poor country initiative, which is being
coordinated by the two Washington-based institutions.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique is one of the poorest nations in the world, with
national income of 135 U.S.Dollars per person last year.
</P>
<P>
At the end of this year, the net present value of Mozambique's
external debt is expected to be 4.95 billion U.S. Dollars or 709
percent of the country's yearly exports.
</P>
<P>
The proposal is due to be discussed by the executive directors
of the bank and the IMF this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
