<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Members Urged to be Prepared for Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African
Development Community (SADC) today urged its member countries to
be prepared for possible poor rains in the 1997-1998 season.
</P>
<P>
Reggie Mugwara, coordinator for SADC food security sector,
said in Blantyre, Malawi, that there is urgent need for the
member countries to map out strategies to deal with the
likelihood of drought during the rain season, reported Zambia
News Agency.
</P>
<P>
"The re-emergency of the Ei Nino phenomenon in equatorial
pacific ocean points to a strong possibility of poor rainfall in
the 1997-1998 season. Based on the latest observation by
climatic experts, SADC food security is maintaining its note of
caution that climatic condition indicators are such that there
could well be adverse impacts on food production during the
forthcoming season," he said.
</P>
<P>
In view of the possible drought, SADC countries should review
current food stocks and logistics of alternative seed supply to
commercial and communal farmers, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also suggested the member countries review external
financial commitments.
</P>
<P>
The existing surface water resources must be taken care of
together with available irrigation equipment, Mugwara added.
</P>
<P>
Should the fear of drought materializes, the member countries
should strive to raise resources to feed their own people instead
of relying on donor aid, said the SADC official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
