<HEADLINE> Jordan Has Mixed Reactions to Albright's Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Jordanians have expressed mixed
reactions to the upcoming maiden visit to the Middle East by
United States Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's aimed at
reviving the stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Abdul Salam Majali said here today that he was
"optimistic" about the long-awaited visit by Albright, Radio
Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that Albright would urge all the parties in the
region to overcome obstacles facing the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Albright's Mideast tour, due to start on September 9, is
expected to include Israel, the Palestinian self-rule areas,
Jordan, Syria, Egypt and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Minister of Foreign Affairs Fayez Tarawneh, however,
has expressed concern that Albright might have a tilt over Israel
while seeking ways to save the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
He said the Jewish woman secretary of state should, during her
visit, propose new initiatives which do not focus solely on the
"security needs" of Israel.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot go back to the terms of reference of (U.S. Middle
East special envoy) Mr. Dennis Ross, where the security issue was
the basic problem," the semi-official newspaper Jordan Times
quoted Tarawneh as saying today.
</P>
<P>
Dennis Ross managed to initiate a series of security meetings
among Palestinian, Israeli and U.S. officials during his visit to
the region in early August shortly after the suicide Jerusalem
market bombings.
</P>
<P>
"The security needs are part of the whole peace process
but not the whole issue," Tarawneh said.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. was the only party that is able to bring the
region a viable initiative while Jordan and Egypt, the only two
Arab countries having peace treaties with Israel, were not
qualified to make such an initiative.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have been in deadlock since
March when Israel broke ground for building a Jewish settlement at
Har Homa in Arab East Jerusalem, where the Palestinians want as
their future capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
