<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK to Seek Tougher Rules on Dumping at Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The British government is
considering to seek tougher international rules on dumping waste
and redundant oil platforms at sea.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a BBC radio interview early today, Britain's
Environment Minister Michael Meacher said the British proposals,
including targets for reduced levels of radioactive waste and
other hazardous substances at sea, would be presented to a
Brussels meeting of the Oslo/Paris Convention.
</P>
<P>
The Oslo-Paris Convention is an inter-governmental organization
monitoring and regulating pollution in the northeast Atlantic from
the Arctic to Gibraltar.
</P>
<P>
"I think this is the most important change in UK marine policy
for at least a couple of decades," Meacher said. "We are making it
clear that Britain accepts the presumption against sea disposal of
redundant oil and gas installations."
</P>
<P>
Meacher noted that dumping oil platforms at sea would be
unacceptable to the Labour government, saying that option would
only be considered for a "small number of cases" covering the
heaviest concrete installations in very deep water or damaged
structures which could be dangerous.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that some 75 percent of Britain's oil and gas
platforms are light installations in shallow water which would
have to be removed during decommissioning under International
Maritime Organization rules.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, environmental activists hailed the British
government's guidelines on dumping at sea with Greenpeace
executive director Peter Melchett rating it " the most dramatic
change in UK marine policy for at least a decade and a half."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
