<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Militia Still Trying to Force S. Leone Junta Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The decision of west African leaders
not to use force against Sierra Leone's military junta has not given
it a chance for a breathing spell as some local militiamen continued
their activities for restoring the civilian government.
</P>
<P>
Traditional hunters known as Kamajors loyal to elected President
Ahmed Tejan Kabbah who was ousted in the May 25 coup, have occupied
the highway between Bo, the second largest city in the south, and the
northern town of Makene.
</P>
<P>
They set up checkpoints along the highway in an effort to capture
personnel and vehicles of the junta as well as its allied ex-rebel
group Revolutionary United Front (RUF).
</P>
<P>
The Kamajors beheaded four people who were suspected of being
soldiers and allies of the junta Monday in northern Sierra Leone,
the British Broadcasting Corporation reported today.
</P>
<P>
The four were travelling in a commercial bus heading for Makene and
were taken at a Kamajor checkpoint in a village 25 miles from Bo.
</P>
<P>
All the four, including the driver identified as a retired soldier,
two men and a women, were executed and the vehicle impounded.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted one of the passengers back in Bo this afternoon
as saying that the Kamajors had vowed to take Bo at any time.
</P>
<P>
The militiamen, said to be in an angry mood, told them that they
were only after the government soliders and RUF rebels, but the
civilians were free to travel without risk.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the brigade commander of the army in Bo admitted that
the Kamajors had occupied the highway but said his troops would soon
"flush them out".
</P>
<P>
The Kamajors have been fighting with the military ever since the
coup, mainly in the southern areas of the country.
</P>
<P>
Repeated fightings have been reported with the armed forces seeming
to gain more than the militia group.
</P>
<P>
The resistant activities of the Kamajors have intensified the
crisis in Sierra Leone, where the junta is facing tightened sanctions
and embargo imposed by west African countries aimed at forcing it to
step down.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
