<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Denies Having Problems With S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Foreign Minister tom
Ikimi today denied that Nigeria has problems with South Africa,
saying that the two countries enjoy cordial relations.
</P>
<P>
Ikimi told this to the News Agency of Nigeria in Pretoria,
where he held talks with S. African President Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
He arrived in S. Africa on Monday to deliver a special message
from Nigerian head of state, General Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
Ikimi accused external forces of trying to paint a false
picture of the relations between Africa's two major powers.
</P>
<P>
He said he discussed sensitive issues of bilateral importance
with President Mandela and that his visit "should send the right
signal to the world that Nigeria and South Africa have nothing
against each other".
</P>
<P>
According to him, General Abacha and Mandela are in regular
contact and has worked closely to find solutions to several
continental problems.
</P>
<P>
Seeming to admit that the relations of the countries are not
without any problems at all, Ikimi further said,"Even the best of
friends could disagree on issues sometimes, but they remain
friends."
</P>
<P>
Later in the day, Ikimi flied to Harare and held talks with
his Zimbabwean counterpart Stan Mudenge. He is also expected to
meet with Zimbabwean president Robert Mugabe, who is also
Chairman of the Organization of African Unity.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that Ikimi's visits to S. Africa and Zimbabwe
are related with the meeting later this month in London of the
Commonwealth Ministerial Action Group (CMAG).
</P>
<P>
Both Zimbabwean Foreign Minister Mudenge and South African
Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo are CMAG members.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is expected to make its recommendations to the
October Summit of the Commonwealth of Nations in Edinburgh,
Scotland, on whether Nigeria will remain in the Commonwealth or
will be expelled.
</P>
<P>
When the Commonwealth suspended Nigeria's membership in
November 1995 for executing Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight other Ogoni
activists, it gave Nigeria an ultimatum of two years to improve
its human rights records.
</P>
<P>
While he was still in S. Africa, Ikimi urged Commonwealth
member countries to guard the ideals of the organization and
avoid it being used as a body for hounding other nations by some
other over zealous members.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed disappointment with the CMAG for holding
talks with Nigerian dissident groups abroad, many of whom, he
said, are responsible for Nigeria's problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Accuses US of Biased Mideast Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Parliament Speaker
Nabih Berri today accused the United States of carrying out a
biased Mideast policy in favor of Israel, the Lebanese official
National News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is unable to get out of the shadow of Israeli policies
on Middle East issues, Berri said during an interview with
Romanian TV. He is scheduled to begin visit to Romania, Armenia
and Iran on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Now that the United Nations Security Council Resolution 425 was
initiated and voted for by the U.S., the speaker asked "why can't
it be observed by Israel, whereas the U.N. sanctions it proposed
against Iraq and Libya can be completely implemented?"
</P>
<P>
The UN Resolution 425 demands Israel to withdraw its troops
unconditionally from south Lebanon it occupied since 1985.
</P>
<P>
Berri said the Lebanese people enjoy good relations with the
Americans, but oppose American policies, because they are not in
the interest of Lebanon and other Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
When asked about his top task for his visit to Romania, he said
he would first thank the Romanian people and government for
supporting Lebanon and the Arab world in their efforts to recover
the lands occupied by Israel.
</P>
<P>
He said Romania and its people have sided with Lebanon and its
people in the implementation of the U.N. Resolution 425. 
</P>
</TEXT>
