<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa to Have Independent News Agency: UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 2 (Xinhua) -- African countries had
offered more than eight million U.S. Dollars for the setting up
of an independent news agency for the continent, an official with
the United Nations said in Pretoria today.
</P>
<P>
Babacar Fall, seconded by the UN to run the process as
co-ordinator-general, said that the South African government
will also take part in the venture and was expected to make a
significant contribution.
</P>
<P>
The new enterprise will culminate from the privatization of the
Pan African News Agency (PANA), which was set up by the organization
for African Unity in 1983.
</P>
<P>
Fall said only 25 percent of the news agency would be owned by
African governments. The rest of the shares would be offered to
African nationals in the private sector, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Dakar-based PANA, which was wholly owned by OAU member
countries, has struggled since its inception because many states
failed to pay their dues.
</P>
<P>
OAU heads of state gave the go-ahead for PANA to be privatized
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
"Democratic changes have been sweeping across the continent, and
PANA has to change accordingly," Fall said.
</P>
<P>
He said it was hoped that the media in the private sector would be
the first to take up shares. Other commercial enterprises, such as
commercial and development banks, were also showing interest.
</P>
<P>
"The only restriction is that all the shares must be in the hands
of African nationals. We must keep the Africaness of PANA intact," he
said.
</P>
<P>
In July, a conference of African Information Ministers in Cairo
decided the privatization process had to be expedited. At that
occasion, a total of 6.7 million U.S. Dollars as pledged by
participating governments.
</P>
<P>
The amount had since grown to about 8.3 million U.S. Dollars and
was expected to rise further as some governments had yet to
decide on the amount they wanted to contribute.
</P>
<P>
The donators included South Africa, for which a number of
symbolic shares had been set aside, Fall said.
</P>
<P>
"We are sure that South Africa will give more than some of the
smaller countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
PANA Press Limited will be established in Dakar on September 26,
Fall said, the news agency will need at least 150 staffers, and
offices would be opened in key cities as soon as possible.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
