<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-02 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More State-Owned Shares to Go Private in Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait will sell 250
million government-owned shares to the public on September 14 in
a bid to accelerate the country's privatization drive launched in
1994, a Kuwaiti official said today.
</P>
<P>
The scheduled sale of the shares valued at about 76.25 million
Kuwait dinars (254 million U.S. dollars) was within the
privatization plan of the state-run Kuwait Investment Authority's
(KIA), Fahad Rashed Al-Ibrahim, KIA chief manager said.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait News Agency quoted him as saying the share offering was
also aimed at implementing the second phase of privatizing KIA's
shares in Burgan Bank, one of the main commercial banks in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The shares, mainly for minor subscribers, will be sold to the
public at the price of 305 fils (a little more than one dollar)
per share. Al-Ibrahim added this batch of shares represents 34
percent of the total shares of Burgan Bank.
</P>
<P>
KIA, the state agency overseeing the privatization program,
has recently privatized 130 million shares of the bank.
</P>
<P>
Since 1994, more than 2 billion dollars has been raised in the
privatization program which set out to sell state shares in some
62 companies and is due to be completed in 1998.
</P>
<P>
However, the program does not include the sale of any major
state-owned utilities, such as water and electricity, nor does
it include the key oil sector, which is the government's main
source of revenue, the manager said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
