<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: Photographers Sued for Death of Princess </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Despite the discovery that the
chauffeur of the late Princess of Wales was drunk when death
descended on her Saturday night, the French judicial authorities
today did not let go the six photographers and one motorcyclist
who were caught pursuing her.
</P>
<P>
They were charged by the Paris Public Prosecutor for
"involuntary homicide and injury" and "non assistance to person in
danger."
</P>
<P>
The photographers are Nicolas Arsov of the Sipa agency, Jacques
Langevin of the Sygma agency, Laslo Veres, an independent
photographer, Serge Arnal of the Stills agency, Romulad Rat of the
Gamma agency and Christian Martinez of the Angeli agency. The
motorcyclist is Stephane Darmon of the Gamma agency.
</P>
<P>
Six of them were released in the evening but were put under
judicial control after being questioned by Judge Herve Stephan of
the Paris Investigation Court. They could face up to five years
in jail and 500,000 francs (83,400 U.S. dollars) of fines if
convicted.
</P>
<P>
After the Public Prosecutor of Paris and the Investigation
Court of Paris decided to begin legal proceedings against the
seven men, their employers and lawyers made an outcry denouncing
the authorities for picking up the photographers as scapegoats.
</P>
<P>
Hubert Henrotte, the director of the Sygma agency, said in a
protest statement published by daily le Monde today that his
employee Jacques Langevin was returning home "in his old car" when
he saw the incident taking place.
</P>
<P>
Out of "good professionalism", Langevin took out his camera and
took the pictures of rescue operation before being arrested by
police, said Henrotte.
</P>
<P>
William Bourdon, the lawyer of Nicolas Arsov, denounced the
decision of the judicial authorities as "justice Quai d'Orsay
(French Foreign Ministry) and justice spectacle, far from the
reality of the reproached infractions."
</P>
<P>
Moreover, a French photographer who joined the chase for Diana
but was not arrested by police today told the German private
television channel Pro Sieben that before the chase began, the
chauffeur of Diana, Henri Paul, shouted to them: "You will not
catch us tonight!"
</P>
<P>
Paul was found to have an over high containment rate of alcohol
in his blood and was driving at 180 kilometer per hour (about 110
miles per hour) when he crashed the Mercedes into a pillar in an
underground tunnel by the Seine river in downtown Paris.
</P>
<P>
The unidentified photographer told the German television that
the Mercedes was "burning with maximum speed like a red fire" and
"took several sways." He said that it was speeding so fast that
the motorcycles could no longer catch it after entering the tunnel
by the Alma Bridge.
</P>
<P>
"While we heard the noise from the accident, we first thought
that it was a bombing attack, because it was like the noise from
the explosion of a bomb. In the tunnel, it was a real massacre,"
said the photographer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
