<HEADLINE> UN Inquiry Team on Alleged Massacres of Rwandan Hutu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. inquiry team
in the Democratic Republic of the Congo could start its delayed
investigations on the alleged massacres of Rwandan Hutu refugees
as the country had dropped its objections, U.N. spokesman Fred
Eckhard said today.
</P>
<P>
"The foreign minister of the Democratic Republic of the Congo,
Bizima Karaha, informed U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan by phone
on Monday that the U.N. human rights investigative team in the
Congo can begin its work," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
"The objections raised in a letter to the secretary-general
signed by two ministers of the government have been dropped,"
added the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the United Nations was awaiting written
confirmation of this and the investigation team was making
preparation to start its work.
</P>
<P>
Human rights groups and aid officials believe that thousands of
Rwandan Hutu refugees were killed by Kabila's troops and their
Rwandan Tutsi backers during their military fighting this year to
topple former President Mobutu Sese Seko. 
</P>
</TEXT>
