<HEADLINE> Pro-Kurdish Activists Barred from Entering Ankara </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish police today
blocked six busloads of pro-Kurdish activists from entering the
capital Ankara, the semi-official Anatolia News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
Those activists planned to stage a sit-in in support of the
Kurds in Turkey and were stopped by the police near the border of
Ankara province.
</P>
<P>
The convoy then drove towards Istanbul, the country's largest
city where they set off from Sunday under a "Peace Train" plan.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government has taken measures to block the plan,
which would take a group of pro-Kurdish Europeans to Turkey.
However, some of them have reportedly entered Turkey through
different ways.
</P>
<P>
In Sanliurfa in southeastern Turkey, security police stopped
seven buses carrying activists including European, U.S. and
African politicians and reporters.
</P>
<P>
The Kurdish issue is a long-standing problem annoying the
Turkish authorities, which also frustrated Turkey's bid for full
European Union membership.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government has been fighting the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK) since 1984, as the PKK seeks to establish
an independent Kurdish state in the southeastern region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
