<HEADLINE> US Warns Israel Against Harming Road Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The United States today
warned Israel not to harm workers on a U.S.-funded road project in
the West Bank city of Hebron on the eve of the first visit to the
Middle East by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Palestinian workers who were working on the
project have been attacked by Jewish settlers with stones,
intended to disrupt the project sponsored by the USAID agency.
</P>
<P>
"These attacks on USAID workers are simply unacceptable and we
call on the Israeli authorities to ensure the security of those
working on the road, so that it may be completed as called for in
the Hebron agreement," State Department spokesman James Foley
said.
</P>
<P>
The incident occurred just a week before Albright is going to
take her first trip to the Middle East to address what she said
was the "crisis of confidence."
</P>
<P>
The road project is in Hebron's Shuhada Street, which links two
Jewish settler enclaves. The street is controlled by Israel but
inhabited by Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Israel handed over most of Hebron to Palestinian self-rule
under a U.S.-brokered agreement in January. The city is inhabited
by 100,000 Palestinians with some 400 Jews residing there.
</P>
</TEXT>
