<HEADLINE> SADC Economies Management Viewed as Satisfactory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The general management of the
economies in the member countries of the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) are satisfactory, a SADC official said today.
</P>
<P>
SADC Finance and Investment Sector Coordinator Bongi Kunene said in
Blantyre, Malawi, that although the macro-economic outlook for the
region varied from country to country, the economies of the member
countries are well managed with structural adjustment program
realizing some success, according to Zambia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Kunene expressed her satisfaction with the foreign investment
coming into the sub-Saharan region.
</P>
<P>
"Compared with the rest of the sub-Saharan Africa, the region has
done well in terms of attracting foreign direct and venture capital
flows," she said.
</P>
<P>
In attracting foreign capital to the sub-region, the sector has
settled for town pragmatic objectives, she said.
</P>
<P>
Kunene said the investment program looked at bankable, viable,
acceptable and manageable projects in the SADC region.
</P>
<P>
SADC stock exchanges established last year will further
provide a framework for regional cooperation in addition to making
national stock exchanges attractive to investors, she said.
</P>
<P>
SADC countries with stock exchanges are Botswana, Zambia, Malawi,
Swaziland, Mauritius, Namibia, Zimbabwe and South Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
