<HEADLINE> Turkey Vows to Block Missiles Delivery to Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Deputy Prime Minister
Bluent Ecevit said today Turkey would use all necessary means to
block the delivery of anti-aircraft missiles purchased by Cyprus
from Russia.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press prior to a government meeting today,
Ecevit said Turkey would closely monitor the Turkish straits
linking the Black Sea and the Mediterranean by checking all ships
sailing through its waters.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit said these measures are aimed at safeguarding the
security of Turkey. Earlier reports said the missiles might be
shipped to the east Mediterranean island through the straits.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus government signed an arms deal in January with
Russia to buy 150 S-300 missiles. Turkey was enraged and
threatened to destroy the missiles if they are deployed.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus government, however, repeatedly said its purchase of
the missiles was for defense, arguing that Ankara has no reasons
to block the arms deal.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Russian side said it had no plan to give up the
arms contract, adding the delivery of the missiles would go ahead
as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
invaded and occupied the northern third of the island in the wake
of a failed coup by Greek Cypriot seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared in 1983 a breakaway "Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus" which is recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
