<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK House Price Inflation Scaled Back to 6 Pct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Britain's biggest mortgage
lender Halifax has scaled down its prediction for the country's
house price inflation this year, said local press reports today.
</P>
<P>
According to Halifax's monthly survey, house prices rose on
average by 0.5 percent to 68,881 pounds (110,898 US dollars) in
August, taking the annual increase to 6.4 percent, unchanged
compared with July and at its lowest level this year.
</P>
<P>
This led the bank to cut its 1997 forecast for annual house
price rises from 7 percent to 6 percent, which, it said, should
ease fears of the housing market overheating after large increases
in house prices reported in London and the southeast.
</P>
<P>
Halifax said that the lower rate of annual growth reflected
higher base interest rates, up one percentage point since the
election, and budget changes to cut the rate of mortgage interest
tax relief from 15 to 10 percent next April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
