<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Diary Of Nanjing Massacre Available In Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Li Xiuying was only 19 years
old in 1937 when she was almost stabbed to death by Japanese
soldiers in her hometown of Nanjing, but the young pregnant woman
survived after she was rushed to a hospital in a safe area.
</P>
<P>
Today, at the age of 79, Li's painful memories have come alive
with the publication of a diary written during the Nanjing
Massacre, when an estimated 300,000 Chinese died.
</P>
<P>
"Today we also want to show our heartfelt respect to Mr. Rabe
for his authentic records of the period," she said at a
publication ceremony, referring to John H.D. Rabe, the author of
the diary.
</P>
<P>
Rabe came to China as the general representative of Germany's
Siemens in 1931 and witnessed the Japanese invasion and the
soldiers' atrocities after they occupied the city in 1937.
</P>
<P>
Elected as chairman of the International Committee of the
Nanjing Safety Zone, Rabe, along with a dozen foreigners, helped
house 250,000 refugees and protected more than 10,000 women from
being raped by Japanese soldiers.
</P>
<P>
He was an eyewitness to the massacre and wrote a 500,000-word
diary and collected some 100 photos to prove that it was committed
by Japanese troops. He returned to Germany in 1938, where he died
of a stroke in 1950.
</P>
<P>
His diary was never made public until his granddaughter, Ursula
Reinhardt, showed it at a press conference in New York in December
last year. Then, Nanjing's Jiangsu People's Printing House and the
Jiangsu Education Publishing House signed a copyright deal last
April with a German a publisher to publish it in Chinese.
</P>
<P>
"The diary and we survivors of the massacre are all
eyewitnesses to history, which nobody can distort," Li said,
pointing to a photo in the diary of the emergency treatment she
received. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
