<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boy Survives, 65 Die in Vietnamese Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, September 3 (Xinhua) -- A Vietnam Airlines plane
crashed today at Pochentong airport in Cambodia, killing all 66
passengers and crew members except one boy.
</P>
<P>
Four people were taken from the wrecked plane alive and were
rushed to hospital, all but the boy died on the way or after
arrival, the Agence France Presse (AFP) quoted a doctor at
Calmette Hospital in Phnom Penh as saying.
</P>
<P>
The agency identified the lucky boy as of Thai nationality, who
suffered a broken right leg and a cut on the head. It said he was
not in a critical condition.
</P>
<P>
The Soviet-built Tupolev-134, carrying 60 passengers and six
crew members, crashed at 1.55 p.m. (0655 GMT) into paddy fields
just off the Pochentong airport, which lies 10 kilometers out of
Phnom Penh.
</P>
<P>
The fuselage was completely torn apart and was engulfed in
flames. Bodies of victims were scattered in the rice field,
witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the victims were believed to be foreigners, but
aviation authorities refused to release a detailed list of them.
</P>
<P>
According to preliminary estimates, the victims were at
least 30 Chinese(including those from Taiwan and Hongkong), 23
South Koreans and other foreigners from Thailand, Vietman, Japan,
Canada, Australia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The plane was on flight VN815 from Ho Chi Minh City in southern
Vietnam to Phnom Penh. It crashed when it was trying to land in
pouring rain.
</P>
<P>
It is learnt that the "black box", the flight recorder, was
already found and an investigation into the cause of the crash is
under way. But officials said the weather might be to blame.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam Airlines operates two scheduled return flights from Ho
Chi Minh City to Phnom Penh on Wednesdays, one in the morning and
one in the afternoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
