<HEADLINE> US Construction Spending Up 0.5 Percent in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Construction spending in
the U.S. increased by 0.5 percent in July, the best showing in the
past five months, U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that the spending increased to a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 598.7 billion dollars in July following a
0.1 percent gain in June, which was revised upward from previously
reported 1.1 percent drop.
</P>
<P>
The gain of U.S. construction spending last month was the
largest increase since last February.
</P>
<P>
The increase in July was led by a 0.9 percent increase in
residential construction which rose to a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of 259.9 billion dollars. Gains in remodeling and
single-family construction more than compensated for a drop in
apartment building.
</P>
<P>
Non-residential commercial construction jumped by 1.2 percent
to an annual rate of 163.9 billion dollars. Gains in the
construction of factories, hotels and churches offset modest
declines in offices, shopping centers and private schools and
colleges.
</P>
<P>
Government construction fell by 0.7 percent to an annual rate
of 136.5 billion dollars. There were declines in highway and
streets and schools, but an increase in sewer construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
