<HEADLINE> Azeri President Orders Closer Cooperation with U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September (Xinhua) -- Azeri President Geidar Aliyev has
ordered government ministries to strengthen their "partnership"
with the United States and develop bilateral cooperation in
politics, economy and security.
</P>
<P>
In a decree to "expand and deepen partnership" with the United
States, Aliyev instructed the government, the Foreign Ministry and
the central bank to work to ensure the implementation of better
cooperation between the two countries and to hand in quarterly
reports on their progress, Interfax news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The president urged his office, the National Assembly and the
Foreign Ministry to open up dialogue in politics, economy and
culture with their U.S. counterparts.
</P>
<P>
He also asked the Foreign Ministry and the Defense Ministry to
work out a proposal for stronger cooperation with Washington over
Azerbaijan's entry into the North Atlantic Treaty Organization's
(NATO) Partnership for Peace Program.
</P>
<P>
The president's order followed his visit early last month to
the United States, during which he and U.S. President Bill Clinton
issued a joint statement vowing to enhance the two countries'
"partnership" by promoting all-round cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Clinton promised Aliyev U.S. support for his country's bid for
membership in the Partnership for Peace Program and an early lift
of sanctions against the central Asian country imposed in 1992
during a war between Azerbaijan and Armenia over the
Nagorno-Karabkh dispute.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, the Azeri national oil company signed eight
billion dollar deals with four U.S. companies on joint exploration
and drilling of Azerbaijan's oil fields in the Caspian Sea.
</P>
