<HEADLINE> EU Grant to Stabilize Chernobyl Tomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
executive body of the European Union (EU), today decided to
allocate 100 million ECUs (130 million U.S. dollars) to prevent
further leakage from the Chernobyl sarcophagus.
</P>
<P>
The EU move follows a decision at the Denver summit of the
Group of Seven industrialized nations in June to provide 300
million dollars of the overall 750 million dollars needed to make
the sarcophagus safe.
</P>
<P>
A team of international experts have found that the
sarcophagus, which covers Chernobyl Unit 4 nuclear reactor which
melted down in April 1986, is in dire need of repairs in order to
prevent radiation leakage.
</P>
<P>
The EU provides technical and financial assistance to the
Chernobyl Nuclear Power Plant for reducing the negative social
impact of the closure of Chernobyl, which still employs 4,000
people.
</P>
<P>
It also provides medical help to the victims of the accident,
including treatment for thyroid cancer in children, and the
rebuilding of a hospital for children.
</P>
<P>
At the Denver summit, the G7 heads of states and governments
and the European Commission endorsed the setting up of a
multilateral funding mechanism to assist Ukraine in transforming
the existing Chernobyl sarcophagus into a safe and environmentally
stable structure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
