<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea Takes Measures to Boost Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 3 (Xinhua) -- South Korea plans to bolster the
sluggish stock market through measures including cutting
stock-brokerage taxes drastically.
</P>
<P>
The government's tax-reduction package, to be formally
announced soon, will also include various incentives for foreign
stock investors, officials at the Ministry of Finance and Economy
(MOFE) said today.
</P>
<P>
The government is considering slashing taxes on investors from
countries without agreement on preventing double-taxation, like
Japan and Germany. Investors from such countries are currently
required to pay 10 to 25 percent of their returns in taxes at home.
</P>
<P>
The government will advance, from October to this month, the
launching of a plan to raise the foreign stock ownership limit from
23 percent to 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
In a policy recommendation delivered to the MOFE Tuesday, the
Korea Securities Dealers Association (KSDA) asked the government
to suspend plans for massive sell-offs of Korea Telecom shares in
the second half of the year and called for expanding the issue of
government bonds.
</P>
<P>
"The government should make greater efforts to minimize new
public offerings in the second half," said the KSDA.
</P>
<P>
The government should be racking brains to work out far more
drastic steps as the stock index was unlikely to recover in the
immediate future, market analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Reflecting the investors' disappointment with the delayed
market-boosting package, share prices edged down nearly 60 points
to a 690-level-low during last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
