<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuala Lumpur Stock Indexes Close at 50-Month Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Kuala Lumpur Stock
Exchange (KLSE) continued to drop today under persistent selling
pressure with share prices closing at a 50-month low.
</P>
<P>
The Composite Index, which opened at 797.06 points, fell to a
low of 747.68 before holding to a close of 750.76 points, 44.97
points lower than the previous closing.
</P>
<P>
The Emas Index lost 9.64 points to 210.29, the Industrial Index
 89.14 points to 1,521.30 and the Second Board Index 10.98 points
to 373.98.
</P>
<P>
Losers led gainers by 660 to 88 while 62 counters remained
unchanged and 74 other issues were not traded.
</P>
<P>
The main board ready turnover decreased to 329.776 million
shares valued at 1.218 trillion ringgit (about 419.9 million U.S.
dollars) from 374.05 million shares worth 1.37 trillion ringgit
(about 472.5 million dollars) yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The second board volume shrank to 31.367 million shares valued
at 238.725 million ringgit (about 82.3 million dollars) from
51.135 million shares worth 409.149 million ringgit (141 million
dollars) yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Off-market deals amounted to 45.895 million shares valued at
407.121 million ringgit (about 140.3 million dollars) from 59.854
million shares worth 181.095 million ringgit (about 62.4 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
KLSE Chairman Nik Mohamed Din Nik Yusoff today called upon
local investors to try their best to maintain the Kuala Lumpur
share market in response to their Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad's call for supporting the local bourse.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian government has announced a number of measures
including barring short sale in the stock market and the
classification of the 100 Composite Index component stocks as
designated counters to arrest market manipulation.
</P>
<P>
Another measure, announced by Mahathir today, is to set up a
60-billion-ringgit (about 20.68 billion dollars) fund to support
the KLSE.
</P>
<P>
If the money is not enough, more would be raised, Mahathir told
a press conference here.
</P>
<P>
He said the government has taken the move to help investors
face problems following the sharp drop in shares prices due to
continued manipulation of the stock and currency markets by
foreigners.  
</P>
</TEXT>
