<HEADLINE> Minimum Income Guarantee For Chinese City Dwellers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- China's State Council is
preparing to put in a minimum cost of living system in urban areas
before the end of 1999, according to a conference held by the
State Council here today.
</P>
<P>
A State Council circular issued a few days ago says that the
people covered by the system are permanent urban residents with a
per capita income that is below the local minimum cost of living,
which is set by local governments. Funding for this will come from
the local government.
</P>
<P>
As China moves toward a market economy, more employees of
inefficient state-owned enterprises have lost their jobs, but
their lives must be protected by a proper social security system
to help state-owned enterprise reforms, State Councilor Li Guixian
said at today's conference.
</P>
<P>
"This system is also a major step toward gearing the
traditional social security system to the socialist market
economy," Li noted.
</P>
<P>
He explained that with China's booming economy, state revenues
are on the rise and that provides a foundation for a social
security system to help those in need.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, a minimum wage guarantee system has been
established in 206 Chinese cities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Announces Measures to Stabilize Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government
today announced a number of restructuring measures to stabilize
the country's economy following the rupiah depreciation against
the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Mar'ie Muhammad, speaking after a limited
cabinet meeting chaired by President Soeharto, said the measures
were aimed at creating a balance in imports and exports, money and
capital markets, and budget and tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
These included maintaining development momentum, continuing a
prudent fiscal and monetary policy by easing the monetary
liquidity and lowering interest rates stages.
</P>
<P>
Mar'ie said that in accordance with the current realities, the
government will soon start revising the budget.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown in the economy resulted in an equally significant
drop in state revenues from taxes. Based on the principle of a
balanced and dynamic budget, state expenditures will also be duly
adjusted so as to avoid a budget deficit, he said.
</P>
<P>
Due to a decreased budget, he noted, certain government
projects have to be postponed or rescheduled.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will also take concrete measures to
increase exports, including granting facilities to exporters and
other export supporting activities within the scope of existing
regulations.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, to discourage imports, luxury sales tax on
non-vital goods will be raised.
</P>
<P>
Apart from state budget projects, he said added, all other
state projects including those of state-owned companies,
particularly with a high import content, will be reconsidered.
</P>
<P>
National banks that are sound but facing temporary liquidity
problems will be assisted, he said, adding that banks which are
clearly unhealthy will be encouraged to merge or be acquired by
sound banks.
</P>
<P>
If this measure fails, such ailing banks will be liquidated in
accordance with existing regulations by giving top priority to the
interest of small depositors, he said.
</P>
<P>
To revive the unhealthy development of the local capital and
money market, the government also plans to abolish the 49 percent
limit to foreign investors in buying shares at the primary money
market, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister requested all related agencies to safeguard the
basic needs of the population and maintain price stability.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's rupiah, like other regional currencies, has come
under fierce speculative attacks following the de factor
devaluation of the Thai baht and the Philippine peso in July.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the rupiah continued to weaken against the U.S.
dollar to drop below the 3,000 level and stock prices also fell by
1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Economists said the depreciation of the rupiah has brought
serious impacts to the Indonesian economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
