<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Patients Urged to Eat Traditional Foods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's herbalist
Sithembile Moyo today advised people with AIDS to concentrate on
traditional foods as they are unrefined and consist of some
healing elements.
</P>
<P>
Moyo told the Zimbabwe News Agency that modern foods were too
refined with chemicals that destroyed the immune system, adding
that manufacturers should reduce the amount of chemicals in foods
or add traditional medicinal preservatives.
</P>
<P>
She advised manufacturers to include remedies to problems such
as acidity caused by labels.
</P>
<P>
The herbalist also urged people infected with AIDS to seek
early treatment from traditional healers so that their lives
could be prolonged.
</P>
<P>
While a remedy for the incurable infection which kills an
estimated 500 people in Zimbabwe every week had not been found,
she said, some traditional medicines could reverse the symptoms
and prolong life.
</P>
<P>
"People have to understand that these symptoms can only be
reversed at an early stage," said Moyo, adding, "Most people
visit us as a last resort when they are very sick. We cannot
help them because their immune system would have been destroyed."
</P>
<P>
Most traditional medicines worked on an immune system that was
still functional, but once this had been destroyed, treatment was
futile, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
