<HEADLINE> UNDP Chief: Peace Prerequisite for International </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 3 (Xinhua) -- UNDP Administrator James
Gustave Speth said here today that large-scale assistance will not
come forth until peace is established in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Describing his negotiations with Afghan Taliban militia as
constructive, Speth, administrator of the U.N. Development Program
(UNDP), said at a news conference here that the world body is keen
to help the people of Afghanistan "as much as we can."
</P>
<P>
However, Speth stressed that major international support for
Afghanistan will depend on a durable peace settlement and
establishment of effective institutions for development
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Referring to his meetings with the Taliban authorities Tuesday
in Kandahar, a major city in southeastern Afghanistan, Speth said
matters pertaining to additional opening of schools for boys and
girls were discussed.
</P>
<P>
Donors are finding it increasingly difficult to provide funds
for a country that has been at war with itself for almost 20
years, said Speth who has been visiting the region since Monday.
</P>
<P>
The international community will be unable to find the funds
Afghanistan needs for rehabilitation and development until
fighting stops, he said.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP, with offices in 132 developing countries, is the
world's largest multilateral source of grant technical assistance.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
