<HEADLINE> Malaysia Sets Up Stock Market Supporting Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia today announced
the setting up of a 60-billion ringgit (about 20.68 billion U.S.
dollar) fund to support the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE).
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad, announcing the step,
said the money would be used to buy shares on the stock market
from Malaysians at a premium to the market price.
</P>
<P>
Shares from foreigners, however, would be purchased at market
prices, he told delegates ahead of the general assembly of the
ruling United Malays National Organization (UMNO) which will begin
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir later told a press conference that 30 billion ringgit
(10.34 billion dollars) would be raised through bond issues while
another 30 billion ringgit would be pooled from other agencies.
</P>
<P>
If the money is not enough, more would be raised, he said.
</P>
<P>
The government has taken the move to help investors facing
problems following the sharp drop in shares prices due to
continued manipulation of the stock and currency markets by
foreigners, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian leader said his country did not depend on foreign
parties to raise the money.
</P>
<P>
"We will raise the money locally and we will overcome the
problem in our own way," he said.
</P>
<P>
Today, persistent selling on the KLSE caused share prices to
close at a 50-month low with decreased volumes with the Composite
Index which opened at 797.06 points, falling to a low of 747.68
before holding to close at 750.76 points, 44.97 points lower than
the previous closing.
</P>
<P>
The main board ready turnover dropped slightly to 329.776
million shares valued at 1.217774 billion ringgit (about 419.9
million U.S. dollars) from 374.050 million shares worth 1.370312
billion ringgit (about 472.5 million U.S. dollars) yesterday.
</P>
<P>
KLSE chairman Nik Mohamed Din Nik Yusoff today called upon the
local investors to try their best to maintain the Kuala Lumpur
share market in line with Mahathir's call to support the local
bourse.  
</P>
</TEXT>
