<HEADLINE> Algerian Police Seize Money-Counterfeiting Ring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Police of the Algerian
province of Constantine seized a money-counterfeiting ring,
Algiers Radio said today.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted sources at Algeria's public security
administration as saying the police Tuesday arrested 19 members of
the 23-person ring, which issued 1.2 million forged Algerian
dinars (about 21,000 U.S. dollars) and 55,000 French francs (about
9,400 dollars), in addition to 400 counterfeit gasoline coupons.
</P>
<P>
The arrested, including university students, government
employees and unemployed people, would be brought up for trial on
charges of affecting the national economy, counterfeiting national
and foreign bank notes, forging car documents and imitating
administrative seals, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
According to the radio, a citizen's complaint about a false
gasoline coupon to the public security administration led to the
arrest of the ring. 
