<HEADLINE> Ramos Asks Congress to Stop Charter Change Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos today asked the House of Representatives to stop floor
deliberation on a resolution calling for the convening of the
congress into a constituent assembly.
</P>
<P>
Senator Leticia Shahani, vice president of the ruling
Lakas-NUCD party, said at a press conference that the president
made the decision after having a meeting with Lakas leaders and
key cabinet members.
</P>
<P>
Ramos asked the lower chamber of the congress to give a greater
impetus to tackling vital economic, social and anti-poverty bills
instead of the charter change bill seeking to extend the terms of
elected officials including the president through a constituent
assembly.
</P>
<P>
However, Shahani said, President Ramos also underscored the
need to hold consultation among the various sectors of the society
to feel the pulse of the people on the issue of charter change.
</P>
<P>
"There is need for our people to be given the opportunity to
pause, to be informed and to reflect on the issue of charter
change, as well as on our economic condition, with greater
sobriety and calm discernment," Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
Shahani clarified that the consultation will not be used to
solicit support for the charter change move, adding that the
country's economic condition, particularly the plunge of the
Philippine peso and the rising interest rates, would also be
discussed.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said Ramos took the step to diffuse the tension
resulting from the debates over charter changes. President Ramos
recently voiced his support for amending the constitution, thus
clashing with the opposition and Cardinal Jaime Sin, who called
for a rally on September 21 to express their anger at charter
changes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
