<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Banker Says Euro Delay No Disaster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The German central bank chief
said today that postponing the launch of a single European
currency from its scheduled date of 1999 would not be a political
or economic catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
Bank president Hans Tietmeyer said: "I simply cannot follow
some arguments which I've heard recently that in case of a delay
of the Euro the sky would fall in over Europe, or that the economy
would fall apart."
</P>
<P>
Tietmeyer was speaking in an interview with a German newspaper.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated the need for strict adherence to the fiscal
requirements for Euro qualification, saying: "If the foundations
are sufficiently stable, then the monetary union would be really
positive for the future of Europe.
</P>
<P>
"But if not, the monetary union could prove to be a conflict
union in the long run."
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that this did not mean that he was
speaking for or against delaying the Euro, adding that a
discussion over the issue was not appropriate for the moment.
</P>
<P>
Only in the spring of 1998 could the overall situation be
sufficiently assessed and decisions made on which countries would
be able to join the Euro, or whether there should be another
timetable, Tietmeyer said.
</P>
<P>
The European Union (EU) is due to launch the Euro on January 1,
1999. The first wave of countries to join the Monetary Union will
be chosen in the spring of 1998, based on EU states' full economic
data in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Under the Maastricht treaty, countries wishing to join the Euro
club are required, among other things, to bring their budget
deficit to less than three percent and overall national debt to
below 60 percent of the gross domestic product. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New EU Treaty to be Signed in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The new European Union (EU)
Treaty, known as the Amsterdam Treaty, will be signed on October 2
in Amsterdam, capital of the Netherlands, by foreign ministers of
the 15 EU member countries.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed today by sources in the Dutch Foreign
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
After the signing, the treaty will have to be approved by the
member countries before it can come into effect.
</P>
<P>
The Amsterdam Treaty is based on the Maastricht Treaty which
was signed in 1992. After 15 months' revisionary work, the 15 EU
member countries held a summit this June in Amsterdam and finally
reached agreement on the draft of the new treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
