<HEADLINE> Uganda to Be Benefited from Warehouse Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- A Europe-based international
organization has granted Uganda, Tanzania and Zimbabwe 7.3
Million U.S. Dollars to assist them in setting up warehouses for
storing cotton and coffee, The New Vision reported today.
</P>
<P>
Rolf W. Boehnke, the Managing Director of the Common Fund
Commodities, said that 3.6 million Dollars of the sum will be
used to promote cotton export from Uganda and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The project will assist local businessmen in establishing
their warehouses to accept cotton and coffee and issue them with
receipts, he said.
</P>
<P>
These receipts could be used as collaterals by banks to extend
loans to the buyers to enable them to expand their business, he
explained.
</P>
<P>
The fund would inject a further 7.0 million U.S. Dollars in
the project once it took off, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Uganda revived its cotton production from zero in 1985 to
100,000 bales in 1996/1997 year. Uganda produced 445,003 bales
(185 kilograms each) of cotton in 1965/1966 year.
</P>
<P>
Cotton and coffee are the main traditional cash earning crops
in Uganda. 
</P>
