<HEADLINE> Chinese, Pakistani Foreign Minister Talks in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier and Foreign
Minister Qian Qichen and Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub
Khan agreed today that the United Nations should reform itself to
improve its ability to safeguard world peace and security and
promote economic development.
</P>
<P>
Security Council reforms should be discussed by UN member
states in a comprehensive, fair, rational, and democratic way.
</P>
<P>
They said that UN Security Council reforms should correct the
lack of representation of developing countries, and the unbalanced
representation between developing and developed countries.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers discussed developing bilateral
friendship and co-operation and international and regional issues
of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that China and Pakistan are friendly neighbors and
have a lasting friendship and that this friendship and co-peration
are the result of unremitting efforts of several generations of
leaders.
</P>
<P>
Since the two countries established diplomatic ties, Qian said,
bilateral exchanges and co-operation in various fields have
continued to develop and Sino-Pakistani friendship is
deeply-rooted in the hearts of the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
Qian praised Pakistan for paying close attention to developing
bilateral relations and voiced appreciation for Pakistan's
valuable support to China on the human rights, Taiwan, and Tibet
issues.
</P>
<P>
Gohar said that the Pakistan-China friendship has great
vitality and has withstood various tests, and the bilateral
relations are all-weather special relations.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral co-operation in various fields is fruitful, he said,
adding that his country is willing to continue the good-neighborly
friendship.
</P>
<P>
Gohar also gave an introduction to the lastest development of
the Afghan situation.
</P>
<P>
Qian expressed concern over this and said that China does not
want to see the chaos of war in Afghanistan lead to unstability in
the region.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China sincerely hopes that all parties in
Afghanistan can stop the armed clashes while considering national
interest, and can reach a national reconciliation through peaceful
negotiations, to form a stable government based on a majority that
can be accepted by all parties.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that China believes the Afghan people can solve
their problem properly without external interference. 
</P>
