<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US, GCC Trade Gap Widens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The trade gap between the
United States and its main commercial partners in the Gulf
jumped by more than nine times in the first half of 1997, mainly
due to higher oil prices, according to official figures available
here today.
</P>
<P>
The gap between the United States and the six Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) member states surged to around 470 million
U.S. dollars in the first half of this year from nearly 50
million dollars in the same period of 1996, the figures by the
U.S. embassy here show.
</P>
<P>
GCC exports to the U.S. climbed to 6.24 billion dollars in
the first half of this year, compared with 5.62 billion dollars in
the same period of last year, while their imports rose slightly
to 5.77 billion dollars from 5.57 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Economic experts here said the increase in the GCC exports to
the U.S. market was caused mainly by higher oil prices. The bulk
of GCC exports to the U.S. are crude.
</P>
<P>
Oil prices averaged more than 19 dollars a barrel in the
first half of 1997, one of their highest levels in nearly a
decade.
</P>
<P>
The United States is a key importer of Gulf oil, receiving
around 2 million barrels of oil per day from the 16-year-old
economic, political and defense alliance which groups Bahrain,
Oman, Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates and Qatar.
</P>
<P>
Washington is also the second biggest single commercial
partner of the GCC after Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
