<HEADLINE> Corrected Version </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
reposition its troops and steps will be taken to hasten the return
of refugees displaced in recent fighting under an agreement
reached during two days of talks between Manila and Muslim rebels
that ended today.
</P>
<P>
President Fidel Ramos, announcing the signing of the agreement
between the government and the Moro Islamic Liberation Front
(MILF), hailed the deal as a "very good step in the peace process
to end the rebel group's 19-year-old armed struggle for a separate
state in the main southern region of Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The two sides inked the accord after another round of low-level
negotiations on September 2-3 in Cotabato city, the southern
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was aimed at "giving further meaning and
substance" to a general ceasefire agreement the two negotiating
panels signed in July by hastening the return of thousands of
civilian refugees displaced by recent fighting in Pikit, North
Cotabato province and Pagalungan, Maguindanao province, according
to local media.
</P>
<P>
The accord also stipulates that government troops shall return
within 15 days to its original positions before June 16 and
continue to secure a local highway to ensure the safety of
travelers.
</P>
<P>
Law enforcement in the area shall be primarily undertaken by
the military with prior coordination and consultation with the
MILF-designated liaison in the area.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said both panels also agreed to meet again on September
10-11 to finalize the implementing guidelines and ground rules of
the general ceasefire agreement.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is a 12,000-member rebel group which is holding
preliminary peace talks with the government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
