<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Living Standard of Rural Chinese Upgrades </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- China's 900 million rural
residents have become a more powerful consumer force whose
earnings, food consumption and living space were substantially
improved over the past five years, according to a survey report
from the State Statistics Bureau (SSB).
</P>
<P>
The average net income of rural residents last year stood at
1,926 yuan per capita, 2.7 times that of 1991, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Their living expenditures also rose to 1,572 yuan, compared
with the 1991 figure of only 620 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the substantial increase in incomes, rural residents
have started showing more interest in higher quality, more
nutritious food. Their meat consumption increased from 12.15 kg
per capita in 1991 to 12.90 kg in 1996, and that of fruit
reached 15 kg per person last year, about 1.3 times that of
1991.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the average living space reached 21.7 square meters
for every rural resident, up 17.3 percent from five years ago.
Compared to the earth and wood cabins dominating the countryside
decades ago, over 89 percent of the newly-built houses are made of
both brick and reinforced concrete.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the expanding buying capability of rural residents
makes them a potential buyer for China's electronic industry. By
the end of last year, there were 88 televisions in every 100 rural
households, 63 percentage points higher than in 1991. A rapid
increase was also recorded in the purchase of refrigerators,
washing machines and cassette recorders in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
The SSB report said that a great change also took place in the
buying mix of rural residents. In the rural households, the
proportion of food spending decreased to 56.3 percent of the total
incomes last year, 1.3 percentage points lower than in 1991.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the spending on education, culture and
entertainment registered a 8.4 percent increase during the past
five years, indicating a substantial improvement of quality of
life in rural areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
