<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Adopt More Incentive Export Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladesh government will
provide incentives to encourage exporters and entrepreneurs to
boost the country's exports, local newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
Any discrepancy in the export-led growth strategy will be
addressed, the newspaper, the Independence, quoted Bangladesh
Commerce and Industry Minister Tofael Ahmed as saying.
</P>
<P>
A proposal for import of raw materials and capital goods
without opening L/Cs (letter of credit) has been endorsed by the
Commerce and Industry Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the new export policy is to cope with the free
market economy and sustain in the international market by
competing with the products of other countries, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce and Industry Ministry has already identified some
sectors like tea, leather and garments, Tofael said, adding that
his ministry has given special emphasis to exploring new export
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
The government is pursuing very liberal export-import policies
and a new policy, to be declared soon, will have short lists of
items banned for export and import, the minister stated.
</P>
<P>
Tofael said the government is not taking any unilateral
decision about the import and export policies, rather it is taking
recommendations from the business community.
</P>
<P>
For the first time, the ministry is going to formulate a
five-year policy replacing the present two-year policy in order to
enable the business community to make long-term plans for
production and exports, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said his ministry emphasized the need to include
strategies in the policy for the export of more value-added
products, diversification of export products, quality and
packaging improvement, increase of productivity and market
expansion.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Premier Li Peng Meets Pakistani Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Premier Li Peng told visiting
Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan today that China
will work closely with Pakistan to establish a comprehensive
cooperative partnership for the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Li extended a warm welcome to Gohar Ayub Khan and noted that
bilateral relations have been developing soundly since the two
countries established diplomatic relations 46 years ago.
</P>
<P>
"We are satisfied with fruitful cooperation between our two
countries in all areas, as well as in international affairs," said
Li. He also thanked Pakistan for its support for China.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the Sino-Pakistan friendship has exhibited
great vitality by standing the test of time and the changing
international situation. He added that bilateral friendship was
fostered by the older generation of leaders in the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He noted: "China will never forget their special contributions
to our friendship."
</P>
<P>
Li also said that China is concentrating on economic
construction which requires a long-term peaceful international
environment, especially in surrounding areas.
</P>
<P>
He said that China attaches great importance to advancing
good-neighborly and friendly relations with its neighboring
countries.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that mankind is approaching the 21st century, a
period during which traditional bilateral friendship and mutually
beneficial cooperation between the two countries will enter a new
phase characterized by mutual trust, comprehensive cooperation and
sustained development.
</P>
<P>
Gohar Ayub Khan expressed full agreement with Li's comment on
bilateral relations. He noted that Pakistan values its friendship
with China and regards the further development of bilateral
friendly relations as a milestone for its foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
Khan said the two countries trust each other, and enjoy
a sincere friendship. He noted that Pakistan is fully confident
that bilateral relations will certainly continue to grow.
</P>
<P>
He conveyed the cordial greetings and best wishes of Pakistani
President Farooq Leghari and Prime Minister Mian Nawaz Sharif to
Chinese President Jiang Zemin and Premier Li Peng. Li also asked
Khan to convey his greetings to the Pakistani leaders.
</P>
<P>
Liu Huaqiu, director of the Foreign Affairs Office of the State
Council and Chinese Vice-Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan also
attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Khan arrived in Beijing on Tuesday as a guest of Chinese
Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen.  
</P>
</TEXT>
