<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Condemns Terrorist Operations in Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said today that Egypt strongly condemned terrorist
operations committed against the Algerian Muslim people.
</P>
<P>
Moussa told reporters that those operations have nothing to do
with Islam but are rather "criminal massacres," according to the
Egyptian Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Moussa expressed confidence that the Algerian government is
capable, with the help of the Algerian people, to face up firmly
to those terrorist acts.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated the Egyptian government's full support for
Algeria's stance towards the massacres perpetrated against the
Algerian innocent people.
</P>
<P>
Arab Interior Ministers' Council Tuesday also expressed concern
over the current incidents taking place in Algeria and declared
its full backing to all efforts adopted by President Liamine
Zeroual to uproot terrorism from the North African country.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Bin Mohammed el-Salem, the Council secretary general,
said on the sidelines of a meeting to draft an anti-terrorism
agreement, that the Algerian government "has all the potential to
fight political violence."
</P>
<P>
In the single worst slaughter in nearly six years of violence
in Algeria, 256 died in the massacre in Sidi Rais, just south of
the Algerian capital of Algiers, overnight last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Algerian government blamed the fundamentalists for the
violence. About 60,000 people have been reportedly killed since
the government in January 1992 scrapped a general election
dominated by the radical Islamic Salvation Front (FIS).
</P>
</TEXT>
