<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Extended Drought to Reduce Fall Grain Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The extended heat wave since
late August has caused drought in areas north of Yangtze River and
will reduce this fall's harvest of maize and cotton, according to
scientists from the China Meteorological Science Institute.
</P>
<P>
When compared to corresponding periods in previous years,
rainfall amounts throughout the country were between 50-90 percent
lower in late August. Most areas in Northwest and North China, as
well as in the upper and middle reaches of the Yangtze River
Valley and the Sichuan Basin recorded a rainfall of less than 10
mm.
</P>
<P>
Average temperatures in the regions were some two to three
degrees centigrade higher than corresponding periods in previous
years, and as a result created drought conditions across the
northern section of the country.
</P>
<P>
Scientists noted that the widespread drought will adversely
affect the irrigation of maize, and hinder the maturity of cotton.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologists predict that the drought will continue through
the first ten days of September in spite of increased rainfall in
some areas in Northeast and south China.
</P>
<P>
Experts say an anti-drought campaign should be launched at the
earliest possible date to keep losses at the lowest level
possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila, Muslim Rebels Fail to Forge Truce Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government and
the separatist Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) today failed
to forge a general ceasefire agreement in their seventh low-level
talks.
</P>
<P>
But they signed another accord on hastening the return of
thousands of war evacuees in the southern province of Cotabato and
Maguindanao, the official Philippine News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement, the government-MILF peace panel said they
will meet again at an unspecified date to "finalize" the ground
rules of the general ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the two-day meeting in Cotabato city, Ghadzali Jaafar,
MILF deputy-chief for political affairs, declared that both sides
had already agreed "in principle" on the guidelines of the
proposed truce.
</P>
<P>
However, in the statement, the peace panel said "the ground
rules shall be finalized during a scheduled meeting on a later
date."
</P>
<P>
The MILF is now the largest anti-government Muslim force
operating in the southern Philippines, with an estimated 25,000
armed members.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leprosy Cases Down in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The number of leprosy cases
in Uganda declined from 1,645 in 1995 to 1,511 in 1996, with its
prevalence rate of 0.76 cases in every 10,000 people, a local
paper reported today.
</P>
<P>
This rate surpassed the target rate set by the World Health
Organization (WHO) of one case in every 10,000 people, according
to today's "The New Vision".
</P>
<P>
Decrease of outbreaks of new cases of the disease was a result
of introducing a new cocktail treatment, the report said, adding
that a total of 10,566 patients have been cured since 1981.
</P>
<P>
The declining of the disease is benefited from the joint
efforts of Uganda National Tuberculosis and Leprosy Program and
the German Leprosy Relief Association.
</P>
<P>
The most successful region in the fighting against the disease
is the south and southeast of Uganda. But still, there are 17 out
of total 45 districts in the country remained the problem areas.
</P>
<P>
Districts Arua in the northwest, Lira and Kitgum in the north
account for 30 percent of new cases in the whole country. Arua
and Kitgum districts are the rebel-haunting areas. Experts
attribute the spreading of the disease to refugee movement.
</P>
</TEXT>
