<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Interior Ministers to Meet in Manila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The interior ministers of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) will soon meet here
to tackle the growing drug-related problems in the region, a
senior government official said today.
</P>
<P>
At the weekly National Press Club Forum Meet, Philippine
Interior and Local government Secretary Robert Barbers said the
ministers will focus their discussions on ways of mapping out a
common strategy to combat the growing drug menace to the region.
</P>
<P>
Barbers did not give an exact date for the meeting, according
to the Philippine News Agency.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN, which is currently chaired by the Philippines, also
groups Malaysia, Thailand, Singapore, Indonesia, Brunei, Laos,
Myanmar and Vietnam. Myanmar and Laos were admitted by the
grouping in July.
</P>
<P>
Despite the continuing campaign against this social menace, the
drug-related problem has reached "an alarming proportion" both in
the Philippines and in the ASEAN region, Barbers said.
</P>
<P>
Quoting figures released by the anti-drug authorities, Barbers
said at least 1.7 million Filipino youth are now drug addicts, a
sharp rise from the level of 20,000 recorded in 1972.
</P>
<P>
Barbers also noted that drug lords and drug syndicates in the
country are now raking in a staggering 250 billion pesos (eight
billion U.S. dollars) annually by engaging in such illegal
activities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
