<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Six photographers and one press motorcyclist, who were in
the first-tier box in the accident of Alma tunnel which killed
Princess Diana, were accused by Judge Herve Stephan of the Paris
Investigation Court of "non-assistance to persons in danger,
involuntary homicide and involuntary injury."
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Liberation, Jacques Langevin, one of the
accused photographer of the Sygma agency, said that he felt like
"falling into a trap."
</P>
<P>
-- According to information obtained by Liberation, the
Algerian government has negotiated with the Islamic Salvation
Front for a ceasefire with it and its armed wing, the Islamic
Salvation Army.
</P>
<P>
Algiers was apparently angered by the announcement last weekend
by the FIS leader Abassi Madani to the United Nations Secretary
General that he would appeal for a stop of violence, because
Madani, released recently from jail, was supposed to make the
appeal on state television.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The debate over the privatization of France Telecom and Air
France has divided the Socialist government headed by Prime
Minister Lionel Jospin, who has to choose between economic
efficiency and the hardline position of some ministers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, by reaffirming his opposition to any privatization
of Air France, Minister of Transport Jean-Claude Gayssot, who is
from the Communist Party, is risking to bring a breakdown of the
management to the company, as President of Air France Christian
Blanc has threatened to resign if the government does not agree
with the merger of Air France and Air Inter.
</P>
<P>
-- The German daily Bild Zeitung has denied a report by the
Associated Press that it had bought the photos of a dying Diana
taken after her fatal accident on August 31 in Paris. The
Hamburg-based daily, which has the largest circulation in Germany,
Tuesday published two photos taken on the site of the accident,
but none of them had any sensational images. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
