<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Police Won't Replace Soldiers in Liberia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria police officers will
not replace the west African peace-keeping force (ECOMOG)
operating in Liberia, the New Nigerian reported today.
</P>
<P>
The official newspaper quoted Defense Headquarters spokesman,
Col. Godwin Ugbo, as saying Tuesday that ECOMOG operations in
Liberia had been a full military exercise from onset.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, it had nothing to do with introducing police from
Nigeria and other west African countries in Liberia, he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman made the remarks in response to reports several
weeks ago that the Nigerian police had drawn up lists of its
officers and men detailed for the exercise in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
He said the issue was not raised at the 20th summit of the
Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) which ended at
the weekend in Abuja, capital of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
According to Col. Ugbo, there were instances where the United
Nations wrapped up their military operations in peace keeping
with inputs from the police.
</P>
<P>
However, "the inclusion of the police in wrapping up some
United Nations operations is normal, as the police assist in
cases of investigations but such is not the case with ECOWAS,"
the spokesman explained.
</P>
<P>
With the last lap of ECOMOG operations centered mainly on
training of the armed forces of Liberia and policing of its
borders, the military was in a better position to carry out such
duties, he said.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG, sent to Liberia in 1990 in the heat of the country's
civil war, has succeeded in disarming and demobilization of the
warring factions, which finally led to the end of the seven-year
hostilities.
</P>
<P>
It is originally planned that ECOMOG will leave Liberia six
months after the elected government was put in place last August.
</P>
<P>
But as the job of restructuring and training of the Liberian
army and police has not begun, the tenure of ECOMOG's stay is
expected to be extended, pending request from the Liberian
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
