<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Slightly Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar
finished a little higher against the U.S. dollar after the release
of June national accounts data today.
</P>
<P>
The possibility of a reduction in official interest rates is
weighing on the market.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed in Sydney at 72.72 U.S. cents, up
from 72.65 locally late yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics figures released today
showed that Australian real gross domestic production on an
average basis rose by a seasonally adjusted 1.2 percent in the
June quarter, making an increase of 3.2 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
Economists said they did not expect the result to change the
Reserve Bank of Australia's (RBA) current easing bias towards
monetary policy and they predicted the bank would ease again by
the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The financial market had been talking of the possibility of a
rate cut this morning, following yesterday's RBA board meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar finished in Sydney at 88.24 Japanese yen
from 88.31, and against the German mark, it was at 1.3369, from
1.3242.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
