<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Airliner Crashes, Killing More Than 60 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, September 3 (Xinhua) -- A Vietnam Airlines plane
crashed today at Pochentong airport, killing more than 60 people
on board, an airline official said.
</P>
<P>
Three people survived, the official said. Witnesses said that
one injured person was rushed away to hospital.
</P>
<P>
The official said that a rescue operation was under way.
</P>
<P>
Initial figures put the death toll at 63.
</P>
<P>
The crash left the wreckage in paddy fields just off the
airport, which lies 10 kilometers from Phnom Penh, sending into
the sky a huge plume of black smoke. The fuselage was completely
torn apart.
</P>
<P>
It was not known if anyone on the ground had been killed, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
The plane, a Russian-built Tu-134, was on a flight from Ho Chi
Minh City in southern Vietnam to Phnom Penh. It was trying to land
in pouring rain when it crashed at 1.55 p.m. (0655 GMT) into a
small house near the airport.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rain and strong wind was thrashing at Phnom Penh at the
time of the crash.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the state-run Vietnam Airlines Penh said in
Hanoi that the flight was VN815, scheduled to land in Phnom Penh
at 1.35 p.m. local time (0635).
</P>
<P>
The airlines' office in Ho Chi Minh City said later that there
were 67 passengers and three crew members on the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Most of the passengers were foreigners, including South
Koreans, Japanese, Australians, Americans, Canadians and Chinese
from Taiwan, China.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam Airlines operates two scheduled return flights from Ho
chi Minh City to Phnom Penh on Wednesday, one in the morning and
the other in the afternoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
