<BODY>
<HEADLINE> August Stock Turnover Down in China's Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The stock indices tracking
the performance of companies listed on the Shanghai Stock Exchange
rose in August but trading declined, according to the latest
official statistics.
</P>
<P>
The Composite Stock Index closed at 1,221.06 points at the end
of August, up 2.63 percent from July. The SSE-30 index, which is
based on 30 blue chips, edged up 1.16 points from July to finish
at 3,760.17 points.
</P>
<P>
Despite the rising indices, stock trading in August plummeted
by nearly 20 percent from the previous month to 84.133 billion
yuan (about 10 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The high-priced shares of relatively well-performing companies
were spurned by investors last month, analysts noted, saying this
is a reflection that Chinese investors are maturing.
</P>
<P>
Trading in B shares, which are issued in China but reserved for
overseas investors, expanded to 3.48 billion yuan in August,
nearly 3.62 times that of July. The index for B shares surged 14.6
percent from July to end at 83.55 points.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics also show that repurchasing and spot
trading in state treasury bonds reached 51.8 billion yuan and 19.8
billion yuan, respectively, in August. The figures were almost
unchanged from July.
</P>
<P>
Fund trading totaled 1.3 billion yuan last month, nearly 50
percent more than in July.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
