<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- A record overnight surge on
Wall Street boosted Australian shares to a higher close, with
frenzied buying at the opening later steadying in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Bill Richmond, a broker with Peake Lands Kirwan, said the
record 3.4 percent jump in the Dow Jones Industrial average had
helped to drive up prices for major stocks.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed 37.1 points up at 2,619.0, a
1.44 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
"The marketplace sees that the gains made by the world markets
are long-term improvements and are sustainable. Last night's
results (on Wall Street) were not an aberration," said Richmond.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index was up 65.3 points at 4,225.7 while
the all resources index lifted 14.4 to 1,364.7 points.
</P>
<P>
Among resource stocks, market bellwether BHP was up 14.8 cents
to 17.008 Australian dollars, off an earlier high of 17.25
Australian dollars, and Rio Tinto rose 25.3 cents to 20.15
Australian dollars while WMC gained 13 to 7.05 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Woodside Petroleum closed at a high for today of 11.30
Australian dollars, up 26 cents, after lifting its interim net
profit by 80 percent to 109.44 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index finished 8.5 points higher at 1,312.0, while
spot gold bullion in Sydney was trading 2.15 U.S. dollars down at
322.20 U.S. dollars a fine ounce.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector closed on a high note, 2.13 percent up, with
National Australia Bank jumping 32 cents to 19.07 Australian
dollars, ANZ rising 31 cents to 9.97 Australian dollars, Westpac
gained 10.3 cents to 7.83 Australian dollars and Commonwealth Bank
rose 54 cents to 15.24 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 328.09 million shares traded worth
712.76 million Australian dollars (513.18 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
