<HEADLINE> Vandals Cause Pipeline Fire in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Fire caused by unknown vandals
has gulped a petrol-carrying pipeline in southwest Nigeria's Ogun
State since late Saturday, local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
As at Tuesday, the fire has not been put out, raising afresh
the issue of fuel crisis in the west part of the country, as the
pipeline was carrying petrol from the Warri refinery to Lagos and
other west states.
</P>
<P>
According to Alhaji Haruna Abubakar, Managing Director of the
Pipeline and Products Marketing Company, the fire may have been
ignited by "some vandals in the process of cutting through the
pipeline to steal the products".
</P>
<P>
Oil industry observers are now disturbed by rising cases of
pipeline vandalization by criminals, local media said, adding
that this year alone, about 40 cases have been reported.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar said that given the rising attacks on pipelines, he
would recommend to the government to impose death penalty for
those caught in so doing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
