<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Official Calls India Priority Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Australian Deputy Prime
Minister Tim Fischer said here today that India is now a priority
market for his country and trade between the two nations is
expected to double to 2.8 billion U.S. dollars over the next five
years.
</P>
<P>
Although exports of major commodities such as coal, wool and
pulses would continue to underpin Australia's trade, further
opportunities are expected to emerge based on complementarities
between the two economies, particularly in the fields of
automobiles, telecommunications and services, the deputy prime
minister said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the 5th Australian-Indian Joint Ministerial
Commission (JMC) meeting, Fischer, also the minister for trade,
said trade in goods between the two countries is now running at
over 1.4 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Indian Minister of State for Commerce B. B. Ramaiah
said there is considerable scope for strengthening commercial ties
through improving market access, examining possibilities of joint
ventures and increasing direct investment.
</P>
<P>
He cited food processing, information technology, software,
pharmaceuticals and the wool industry as areas where new
opportunities might open up for further joint venture projects.
</P>
<P>
India's high growth path and its economic reform process offer
tremendous prospects for Australian investment, particularly in
its infrastructure and mining sectors, Ramaiah said.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day meeting, which ended today, the two
ministers also discussed Australia's tariffs on textile, clothing
and footwear products.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement issued today, the two ministers welcomed
the growth in services trade, particularly in the area of
education.
</P>
<P>
Australia is now the second most preferred destination for
Indian fee-paying students, according to the statement.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
