<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Rapists to Face AIDS Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 3 (Xinhua) -- South Africa, troubled
with increasing rape cases and AIDS patients, may force all
convicted rapists to receive HIV/AIDS tests in order to inform
the victims, local daily the Citizen reported today.
</P>
<P>
The compulsory measure was on cards following approval in
parliament's Justice Committee on Tuesday of new laws against
aggravated rape, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The committee had asked the Department of Justice to prepare a
report on the possible criminalization of deliberate acts by
HIV/AIDS sufferers where these endangered the lives or safety of
others.
</P>
<P>
The instruction was made during the endorsement in principle
by all parties in the Justice Committee of the Criminal Law
Amendment Bill, which provides for life imprisonment for a
scheduled of "heinous crimes".
</P>
<P>
These include aggravated murder, rape and armed robbery.
Aggravated rape includes serial rape, gang rape and rape by a
person knowing he was HIV/AIDS patient.
</P>
<P>
The ruling African National Congress and Opposition parties,
including National Party, Inkatha Freedom Party and Democratic
Party, have endorsed the proposals.
</P>
<P>
The number of AIDS cases in South Africa is expected to
increase dramatically over the next 10 years and more than 90,000
AIDS-related death are predicted next year, according to a latest
medical survey.
</P>
<P>
To make things worse is that rape, which put victims in more
dangerous position in the process of sexual intercourse by AIDS
carriers, has in recent years become one of major crimes in South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Police authorities said that last year witnessed at least
12,938 cases of rape and attempted rape, 88 of statutory rape and
1,083 of indecent assault.
</P>
<P>
The incidence of rape had increased almost 20 percent, which
was described by security and medical officials as "an alarming
phenomenon" in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
