<HEADLINE> South African Committee Paid for IOC Wives' Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAUSANNE, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The National Olympic
Committee of South Africa (NOCSA) admitted on Wednesday it had
offered to fly the 20 International Olympic Committee African
members' wives to Lausanne.
</P>
<P>
"Only three or four wives accepted," NOCSA treasurer Kurt
Hipper added. "We don't believe this contravened any IOC rules
whatever. It was done openly and documented. We wanted to give
wives the chance of sharing in what may be an historic occasion."
</P>
<P>
Africa has never staged the Games.
</P>
<P>
The committee paid for first class return air tickets. It did
not pay hotel bills.
</P>
<P>
Bidding cities are limited to making gifts worth 200 dollars to
IOC members.
</P>
<P>
"It was not a secret," Hipper said. He said Cape Town
represented an African bid supported by the Supreme Council for
Sport in Afrca and the Organisation for African Unity.
</P>
<P>
The Cape Town Bid Committee had denied on Tuesday it had
offered to pay for the trip. 
</P>
</TEXT>
