<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agassi's Title Dream Faded at U.S. Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Andre Agassi of the United
States failed to reach the semi-finals when the former world
number one was ousted by 13th-seeded Patrick Rafter of Australia
in four-set 6-3, 7-6(7/4), 4-6, 6-3 in New York on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The loss ended Agassi's Cinderella dream of matching his 1994
title run, in which he became the only unseeded player in the open
to win the championship.
</P>
<P>
Agassi, who was called by Pete Sampras as title favorite, had
missed this year's other Grand Slam events, skipping the
Australian Open to rest and being sidelined from Wimbledon and the
French Open with an injured wrist that kept him out for two months.
</P>
<P>
Agassi had slumped to 63rd on the world rankings, his lowest
level in 11 years. With the loss in the U.S. Open, his ranking
will take another tumble.
</P>
<P>
Agassi called his serve "horrendous" and said he did not play
well until he was too far behind. And he also expressed that the
ATP ranking was not something he thought much about. "Never have,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
