<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grasslands Emerging as Major Ecological Zones in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, September 3 (Xinhua) -- China's vast grasslands, which
cover 400 million ha., or 40 percent of the nation's total land
area, have emerged as increasingly important ecological zones.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a recent national symposium on animal husbandry
held in Urumqi, Vice-Minister of Agriculture Zhang Yanxi said that
major problems in pastoral areas are related to population,
resource management and environmental protection, with the key
problem centered on maintaining a sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
Zhang stressed that developing animal husbandry represents the
best choice for ensuring sustainable development in pastoral areas.
</P>
<P>
The vice-minister noted China ranks second in the world,
following Australia, in terms of grasslands coverage.
</P>
<P>
The 14 million ha. of grasslands planted in China in recent
years have played an important role in improving the ecological
environment.
</P>
<P>
China's grasslands extend northwards and eastwards from the
Qinghai-Tibet Plateau to the western end of the Greater Hingan
Mountains. The green belt not only plays an important role in
water and soil conservation at the sources of Yangtze and Yellow
rivers, the country's two longest rivers, but is also extremely
important in blocking severe winds and sand moving, as well as
controlling the climate and purifying the air.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that vegetation coverage on the Qinghai-Tibet, Loess
and Inner Mongolia plateaus has a great influence on surface and
groundwater resources in northern and eastern parts of China, as
well as Yangtze and Yellow river basins. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Schedules Treasury Bond Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- China will issue 13 billion
yuan (about 1.56 billion US dollars) in ten-year treasury bonds
between September 5-24, the Ministry of Finance announced today.
</P>
<P>
The bonds, the last batch of registered bonds this year, carry
a coupon rate of 9.78 percent and can be traded immediately after
the issue closes.
</P>
<P>
The ministry announcement said that the interest rate was
decided Tuesday through price bidding among more than 70 state
treasury bond underwriters.
</P>
<P>
The Investment Bank of China was the lead underwriter; the two
deputy underwriters were the Everbright Bank of China and the
Shanghai Urban Cooperative Bank.
</P>
<P>
China's state treasury bond issue this year has been budgeted
at 248.5 billion yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
