<HEADLINE> China's Shanghai Keen to Develop Capital Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's leading
financial and economic center, will make greater efforts to
develop its capital market in order to meet the requirements for
being an international metropolis, a municipal planning official
said.
</P>
<P>
To achieve the major economic objectives, Shanghai must invest
an annual average of 200 billion yuan in fixed assets in the next
few years, the official said, adding that the total value of such
investment can be greater than one trillion yuan for the whole
Ninth Five-Year Plan period (1996-2000).
</P>
<P>
In another analysis, Shanghai will invest some 300 billion yuan
in infrastructure construction, including the building of the
Pudong International Airport and a second subway system.
</P>
<P>
Three multi-billion dollar projects will be launched in the
coming years in the Pudong New Area, an emerging financial and
trade district.
</P>
<P>
Official estimates have put Shanghai's needed investment in
ecological and environmental projects to the end of this century
at more than 40 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The official noted that a huge amount of funding is also
required to build new houses with a combined area of 10 million sq
m in order for the living space per urban resident to reach 10 sq
m.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the reform of the state-owned sector, which accounts
for 70 percent of the municipal economy, also needs a considerable
financing, the municipal planning official said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
