<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four Pupils Wounded in Nigerian Bomb Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Four school children were
severely wounded on Tuesday morning when a blast rocked the
convoy of the military administrator of Ekiti state in
southwestern Nigeria, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Lt. Col. Mohammed Bawa, the administrator escaped unhurt while
one of the pupils lost an eye, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
The blast occurred at around 9:45 a.m. when the convoy was
about 150 meters away from the state government house.
</P>
<P>
Bawa was on his way to the office, while the injured were
going to take entrance examination into secondary school at the
time of the explosion.
</P>
<P>
About 30 persons were arrested for questioning, including a
lame man, found within the government reservation area vicinity
after a 15-minute search by security men, and were taken to the
Security Department of the administrator's office for
interrogation.
</P>
<P>
Bawa's official vehicle and two others, including that of the
chief security officer, were destroyed by the blast which
violently rocked buildings nearby.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's explosion was the 14th since the May 31, 1995 blast
at the Ilorin stadium in Kwara state, western Nigeria. It was
also the second involving a military administrator.
</P>
<P>
The first blast against an administrator took place on
December 16 last year, which was targeted at Col Mohammed Mawa of
Lagos state.
</P>
<P>
Ekiti was one of the six states created by the military regime
last October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
