<HEADLINE> Mount Wuyi City Ruins Open to Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, September 3 (Xinhua) -- City remains dating back 2,000
years and found near Mount Wuyi, a famous scenic site in east
China's Fujian province, have been listed as a major attraction
along major local tourism routes.
</P>
<P>
The city, built during the Han dynasty (206 BC-220 AD), was
once the largest ancient city in southeast China. The ruins, which
were discovered in 1958, have been partially excavated.
</P>
<P>
The tourist itinerary will include visits to restored palaces,
city gates, and other Han structures. The historic ruins of the
residences of common people will form a museum of folk arts and
customs. 
</P>
