<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poor Mountain Area Turns Into Rising Economic Center (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The "village of fine
buildings," located in the heart of Dabie Mountains, one of the
most impoverished areas in China, is once again living up to its
name after decades of being covered with thatched huts.
</P>
<P>
Surrounded by a forest of pine trees and a clear river, the
village is dotted with row upon row of newly-built brick-and-tile
buildings. Nearly half, or 240, of the families in the village
have built their own homes, and the rest of the villagers plan to
follow suit.
</P>
<P>
The village got its nickname when a local landlord built a
two-story house in old China -- a tremendous accomplishment in
an area where people did not have enough food and clothing.
</P>
<P>
For years, the building stood out amid the cluster of
weather-beaten houses made of straw and earth, occupied by
ordinary farmers.
</P>
<P>
But recently, more and more farmers in the Dabie mountainous
areas have replaced the traditional thatched dwellings with
brick-and-tile bungalows and later with multi-story buildings.
</P>
<P>
"This suggests that this poor land is catching up with other
parts of the country and heading for prosperity," said Huang
Haisong, an administrative commissioner of Xinyang Prefecture,
which is situated north of the Dabie mountains.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that China has 18 poverty-stricken
areas, 16 of which are mountainous, with a combined population of
58 million, who are in need. Dabie Mountain, which borders Henan,
Hubei and Anhui provinces, is one of them. Some 4.93 million
people living there have been left nearly destitute because of
poor transport facilities and a shortage of money, information and
expertise.
</P>
<P>
During rimes of war, the Dabie mountain area served as a
revolutionary base.
</P>
<P>
The 14-year anti-poverty drive launched by the central and
local governments has increased local farmers' annual income in
Xinyang Prefecture to 1,356 yuan (163 US dollars) and reduced its
poor population from 2.57 million to 473,000 by the end of last
year, Huang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poor Mountain Areas Turns Into Rising Economic Center (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Since 1986, the central government has sent more than 30,000
agro-scientists to help spread 2,600 practical farming skills,
which has turned the Dabie mountainous area into a rising economic
center in central China.
</P>
<P>
With expertise imparted by the experts, the mountain range has
become a "green bank" which can help raise peoples' income with
little investment. Fur, Ginkgo, chestnuts, tea, fish and turtles
are inexhaustible sources of income.
</P>
<P>
Over 70 percent of the people in Xinxian County, formerly the
most impoverished region in Dabie Mountain area, have quadrupled
their annual income by growing fruit and processing mountain
products.
</P>
<P>
A Japanese company has invested 24 million yuan (2.9 million US
dollars) to build a tea processing workshop with an annual
production capacity of 600 tons. A Ginkgo processing plant will
soon be built in the county with 320,000 US dollars of World Bank
loans.
</P>
<P>
The prefecture has led all other areas in Henan province in
economic growth for three years running and is expected to gain an
annual growth of 13 percent in gross domestic product for the
coming four years.
</P>
<P>
It plans to lift all local poor people out of poverty next
year, hitting the national target two years ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
Huangchuan, a riverside county, got wealthy from water,
emerging as the largest duck-breeding center in China, raising six
million ducks every year.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, the county used British loans to build a joint venture
which includes a hatchery, a breeding center, a fodder plant and a
duck down factory. Half of the venture's products are for
export. Its pre-tax profit is to reach 35 million yuan (4.2
million US dollars) after completion of an expansion project in
the near future.
</P>
<P>
Infrastructures in Dabie Mountain area have been improved
markedly in recent years to keep up with economic growth. Two
trunk railways, which link Beijing-Guangzhou and Beijing-Kowloon,
run through the area. Three national highways and an expressway
have been extended to the area. And a power plant with a capacity
of 600,000 kw is being built in Xinyang County.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
