<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Airliner Crashes, Killing More Than 60 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, September 3 (Xinhua) -- A Vietnam Airlines plane
carrying 60 passengers and six crew members crashed today at
Pochentong airport, killing more than 60 people on board, an
airline official said.
</P>
<P>
Three people survived, the official said. Witnesses said that
one injured person was rushed away to hospital.
</P>
<P>
The official said that a rescue operation was under way.
</P>
<P>
Initial figures put the death toll at 63.
</P>
<P>
The crash left the wreckage in the paddy fields just off the
airport, which lies 10 kilometers from Phnom Penh, sending into
the sky a huge plume of black smoke. The fuselage was completely
torn apart.
</P>
<P>
It was not known if anyone on the ground had been killed, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
The plane, a Russian-built Tu-134, was reportedly on a flight
from Ho Chi Minh City in southern Vietnam to Phnom Penh. It was
trying to land in pouring rain when it crashed.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rain and strong wind was thrashing at Phnom Penh at the
time of the crash.
</P>
<P>
A Vietnam Airlines official in Phnom Penh said one of its
planes crashed. But the airlines' officials in Hanoi, capital of
Vietnam, could not give immediate confirmation of the accident.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam Airlines operates two scheduled return flights from Ho
chi Minh City to Phnom Penh on Wednesday, one in the morning and
the other in the afternoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
