<HEADLINE> Iran, Turkey Tackle Diplomatic Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami today received a message from his Turkish counterpart
Suleyman Demirel on the solution of the diplomatic crisis after
expulsion of ambassadors from each side in February.
</P>
<P>
The content of the letter has not yet been published but it is
believed to be an important message concerning the resumption of
full diplomatic ties between Ankara and Tehran, a well-informed
source said here today.
</P>
<P>
The message was delivered by Ali Tuyagan, deputy under-
secretary of the Turkish Foreign Ministry, who arrived here
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
He held talks with Mohsen Amin-Zadeh, Iranian deputy foreign
minister in charge of Asia-Pacific affairs, before delivering the
message to the Iranian new president this morning.
</P>
<P>
The Ankara-Tehran relations took a sour turn in February as
the two governments ordered to kick out envoys from each side
within a week.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian Foreign Ministry ordered Turkish ambassador Osman
Koruturk and Consul General Ufuk Ozsancak leave Iran in a
tit-for-tat measure against the Turkish government.
</P>
<P>
The crisis between the two countries began when Ankara
protested to Tehran in early February about Iranian ambassador
Mohammad Reza Baqeri for his reported comments in favor of
Islamic law at an Islamist rally in the Ankara district of
Sincan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
