<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Fights Against Hot Island Effect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 3 (Xinhua) -- This east China metropolis
has beefed up its efforts to fight against the "hot island effect" by
increasing its afforestation rate and controlling the total number
of motor vehicles in the city.
</P>
<P>
Over the past three years, more than 700 ha of public green
space has been added to Shanghai's landscape, an amount that
equivalent to the total built in the previous two decades. The municipal
authorities also raised the quotas for the area to be covered by
plants in each residential quarter.
</P>
<P>
While strictly reining in the total number of motor vehicles,
the city also set stipulations on the installation and use of air
conditioners, another major urban heat source.
</P>
<P>
Studies have shown that the "hot island effect" first appeared
in Shanghai in the 1980s, as a result of the growing population,
increasing number of buildings, surging consumption of energy, and
shrinking green space and water surfaces.
</P>
<P>
The problem was exacerbated in recent years with the growing
popularity of glass exterior buildings, motor vehicles and air
conditioners.
</P>
<P>
Remote sensing photos and statistical charts show that there is
a clear line of demarcation between the temperatures of the
downtown and the outskirts. On a clear and windless summer day,
the urban temperature can be 4.5 degrees centigrade higher than
the suburban.
</P>
<P>
Local meteorologists have suggested several measures to
alleviate the situation, such as curbing the construction of new
highrises, expanding the area of urban green space and controlling
heat emission from industrial enterprises and motor vehicles and
air conditioners.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Institutions Part of China's Financial Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 3 (Xinhua) -- As more foreign-funded
financial institutions set foot on China and their business
continues to expand, they have proved an indispensable part of the
country's booming financial industry.
</P>
<P>
In 1979, the Export Import Bank of Japan opened its office in
Beijing to become the first foreign financial body in China.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the first half of this year, 540 foreign-funded
financial institutions had been set up in 23 Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
Currently, all economically-developed areas have
overseas-funded financial bodies which have been involved in many
of the pillar industrial sectors in China, such as energy, steel
and iron, telecommunications, automotive-manufacturing and
petrochemicals.
</P>
<P>
Of these foreign-backed financial institutions, banks are
making an eye-catching advance. By the end of June, the total
capital of overseas banks in China stood at 32.96 billion US
dollars, with 23.08 billion US dollars in outstanding loans and
3.99 billion US dollars in remaining deposits.
</P>
<P>
These banks, with well-operating foreign-funded enterprises as
their main clients, normally produced profits in their first or
second year of operation.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1996, the People's Bank of China, the central
bank, approved eight foreign bank branches in Shanghai's Pudong
New Area to open RMB yuan business, and one more was added to the
list early this year. Up to now, seven foreign bank branches have
started the business, which has been operating smoothly so far.
</P>
<P>
A local economist observes that the entrance into the Chinese
financial market by foreign banking institutions has helped lead
China into market-oriented and standardized management concepts
and operational systems and means.
</P>
<P>
As a result, it has further perfected and deepened the
functions of the Chinese financial market, pushed forward the
reform in the country's foreign exchange controlling system, more
effectively enlarged the scale of indirect financing in the
country, and bolstered direct investment by foreign investors, the
economist says.
</P>
<P>
He also points out that the arrival of foreign financial
institutions has brought about changes to China's financial
industry, motivated local banking bodies to accelerate their
restructuring pace, and created a reasonable level of competition
in the industry.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
