<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yunnan Protects Nature Reserves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Yunnan
Province has effectively improved the protection of nature
reserves in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The number of nature reserves has almost tripled from 30 to 87
over the past five years, with the total area growing from 1.34
million ha to 1.71 million ha and accounting for four percent of
Yunnan's total territory.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan has five national, 40 provincial and 42 prefectural
nature reserves.
</P>
<P>
"The establishment of natural reserves has become an important
way to protect wild flora and fauna and the environment in a world
in which related resources are under an increasing threat." said
Shi Jiwu, an official with the provincial Committee for the
Protection of Wild Animals and Plants.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan, an inland province lying at a low latitude, boasts an
abundant array of wild animals and plants.
</P>
<P>
Surveys show that Yunnan is home to 1,638 species of wild
vertebrates and more than 15,000 species of higher plants, or 40
percent and 50 percent of China's total respectively. Some 199
(59.4 percent) wild animal and 151 plant (42.6 percent) species
are under national protection.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan's nature reserves provide a haven for wild plants and
animals, said Shi.
</P>
<P>
Protected nature reserves have raised the number of Asian
elephants to 250, Yunnan snub-nosed monkeys to over 600, gibbon to
over 400, and takin to over 300. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
