<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Kenya's Opposing Parties Committed to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The majority members of
parliament from the ruling Kenya African National Union (KANU)
and the Opposition have reiterated their commitment to dialogue
over constitutional reforms.
</P>
<P>
At the on-going second meeting of the Inter-parties
Parliamentary Group (IPPG) which opened here on Tuesday, 92 MPs
declared themselves the only legal entity to spearhead dialogue
effectively.
</P>
<P>
The participants at the meeting which is going on this morning
passed a resolution binding themselves to the process of
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The resolution says, "we are unequivocally committed to the
current dialogue on legal, administrative and constitutional
reform through the Inter-parties Parliamentary Group".
</P>
<P>
Assistant Minister Jone Osogo who chaired the meeting pointed
out that those attending the meeting had not been forced or
coerced to do so but were guided to look for ways of saving Kenya
from sliding into anarchy.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet Minister Nicholas Biwott from the ruling party told
the meeting that dialogue between the opposing sides was the only
way out for Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Another Cabinet Minister Simeon Nyachae noted that KANU MPs
had had consultations on the reform issues and had endorsed
dialogue among the members of parliament to facilitate changes.
</P>
<P>
Kijana Wamalwa, chairman of the opposition Ford-Kenya, said
that the overwhelming majority of Ford-Kenya members back
dialogue and reforms.
</P>
<P>
"Kenyans want to sit and discuss reforms but not to throw
stones over reforms," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The second meeting is discussing, among other things,
constitutional, legal and administrative reforms, peace and
security in the country, and the general elections to be held
later this year.
</P>
<P>
The first meeting was held last Thursday and resolved to
appoint an Inter-parties Parliamentary Committee of thirteen
members to coordinate the IPPG activities and meetings.
</P>
<P>
The committee was renamed the Coordinating-Working Committee
of the IPPG which is composed of members from the ruling party
and opposition parties Ford-Kenya, Ford-Asili, Democratic Party
and Kenya Social Congress.
</P>
<P>
Prior to Thursday's meeting, the dialogue between the ruling
KANU and Opposition parties brokered by religious leaders had
stalled after KANU refused to talk to the National Convention
Executive Council (NCEC), an umbrella body of Opposition parties,
saying that the body was not elected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
