<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Countries Need to Close Agro-Industry Gap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Member states of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) need major
structural adjustment to close the labor productivity gap between
agricultural, industrial and service sectors.
</P>
<P>
A SADC report said the gap made the sectors stand like two
worlds far apart with a significant decline in both production
and employment in the agricultural sector, local press today
reported.
</P>
<P>
The SADC report attributed poor labor productivity in
agriculture to negligence by policy makers who put all the
emphasis on manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
Entitled "Productivity Key to Sustainable Development in
SADC", the report indicated that attaining a balance in labor
productivity between agriculture, manufacturing and services in
SADC economies was crucial to prepare the countries for the
challenges of the next century.
</P>
<P>
Most SADC member states were still struggling to meet basic
human needs to alleviate absolute poverty, the report said,
adding that the shift to manufacturing and services had to be
accompanied by improvements in agricultural production and
especially subsistence farming.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural productivity in the region was low not only
because of large numbers of people still being employed in the
sector but also because of inappropriate technologies, poor
organization and limited physical and human capital inputs,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The report stressed that SADC member states must in
priority take measures to curb food insecurity through improved
agricultural output per capita. The earlier this happens, the
sooner they will be able to focus resources on new projects and
eventually move to industrial, secondary and tertiary sectors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
