<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forest Park Built on Famous Mountain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The recent completion of the
first-phase project of the Mount Wudang National Forest Park
provides a new must-see destination for visitors to this sacred
mountain of Taoism, a traditional Chinese religion.
</P>
<P>
The 2,000-ha forest park has 50-some scenic sites of human and
historic interest. Visitors can also find more than 50 rare
species of animals such as snub-nosed monkeys, giant salamanders,
and macaques, as well precious plants.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the park started in 1992, said park manager
Wang Nongji, and more than seven million yuan (843,000 US dollars)
has been invested in building high-voltage power transmission lines,
communications and transportation facilities, and a
4,000-sq-m hotel.
</P>
<P>
The park has received about 10,000 visitors since 1995.
</P>
<P>
The second and third phases of the project require a total
investment of about 10 million yuan (1.2 million US dollars), Wang
said, adding that foreign funding is likely to be used.
</P>
</TEXT>
