<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Funds Needed for Ancient Temple Renovation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The east China city of Xiamen
is seeking funds to continue the renovation of a 1,300-year-old
temple which has been damaged repeatedly by fire or in wars.
</P>
<P>
The Fantian Temple, constructed during the Sui Dynasty
(581-618), attracted large numbers of religious pilgrims. Major
fires have twice broken out there, and some remaining buildings
were eventually removed during the "Cultural Revolution"
(1966-1976).
</P>
<P>
The city government decided in 1991 to place the temple's
reconstruction on its agenda, and the project started three years
later.
</P>
<P>
The first-phase work reportedly has been finished, with more
than 12 million yuan of donations, partly coming from overseas
Chinese. Four main rooms have been rebuilt, which are linked by
corridors and bell-drum towers, as well as a road leading to the
temple and a square named after the temple.
</P>
<P>
The second-phase work is now under preparation. The total
funding for the whole work is estimated at 30 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
An inauguration ceremony of Buddha images of the temple will be
held on September 24.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Government Supports Grain Reserve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian
government has allocated 5,000 million shillings (about 8 million
U.S. dollars) to beef up the nation's Strategic Grain Reserve
(SGR), the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Kingunge Ngombale-Mwiru, Chairman of the
Special National Food Shortage Committee, as saying the SGR has
been directed to increase the national food reserve to avert the
impending food shortage following delays of the long rains in the
country.
</P>
<P>
After his recent visit to drought hit areas, Ngombale-Mwiru
said that food situation in the country is bad. He cited Arusha
region as an example, which can only supply 52 percent of its
food needs and the deficit has to be imported from elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
He asked Tanzanians to preserve food "because the shortage
will haunt us until February or March next year," saying the 13
regions hit by drought will need 916,000 tons of food.
</P>
<P>
Ngombale-Mwiru, who doubles as the Minister of State in the
Prime Minister's Office responsible for Mass Media and Policy,
urged an immediate halt to those smuggling food across the
borders. "We cannot allow these people to starve our people
because of their greediness," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
