<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean President to Attend Summit on Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe will leave here this afternoon for Arusha, Tanzania to
attend a two-day summit to discuss economic sanctions imposed on
strife-torn Burundi in July last year.
</P>
<P>
A government statement said Mugabe was invited to the meeting,
to be attended by leaders of the Great Lakes region, in his
capacity as the current chairman of the Organization of African
Unity.
</P>
<P>
He will be accompanied by Foreign Affairs Minister Stan
Mudenge.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, former Tanzanian president Julius Nyerere
will present a report on the negotiations for the restoration of
democracy in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
The talks were aborted on August 25 this year, after Burundi's
Tutsi-led government accused Nyerere, the mediator in the
conflict, of being both the judge and the jury in the war which
has left over 150,000 people dead.
</P>
<P>
Sanctions were imposed on Burundi on July 31 last year, a week
after Major Pierre Buyoya's military junta seized power from
Sylvestre Ntibantunganya, a Hutu, in a bloodless coup d'etat.
</P>
<P>
A report on the ministers's technical committee meeting held
in the Ugandan capital, Kampala on August 16 this year will also
be presented during the Arusha meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Technical Committee on Sanctions on Burundi comprises
foreign affairs ministers of Zambia, Tanzania, Democratic
Republic of Congo, Uganda, Ethiopia, Kenya and Rwanda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
