<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt: Releasing Israeli Spy Impossible </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa has made it clear that it is impossible to overthrow an
Egyptian court decision that has convicted an Israeli of spying.
</P>
<P>
He was defending the judiciary verdict of the Azam Mot'ab Azam
case against the Israeli criticism that the ruling is unobjective,
according to Egypt's leading Al-Ahram daily today.
</P>
<P>
The Higher State Security Emergency Court sentenced Azam, an
Israeli textile engineer accused of spying for Israel, to 15 years
in prison at hard labor on August 31.
</P>
<P>
The court decision is unappealable and Azam could only be
released at the amnesty of Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
Moussa was quoted as telling reporters here Tuesday that the
espionage case is not a topic that concerns Egypt and Israel only,
but rather a phenomenon existing in all countries.
</P>
<P>
"Any spy gets his or her punishment whether he is an Israeli
spy working in the U.S. or Egypt or any country else," said he,
adding that none of the spies can enjoy a special standing.
</P>
<P>
The same court also ruled that Azam's Egyptian colleague, Emad
Abdel Hamid Ismail, be imprisoned for life.
</P>
<P>
Two Arab-Israeli women Zahra Youssef and Mona Ahmed Shawahnah,
standing trial in absentia, were also sentenced to life
imprisonment on charges of recruiting the Egyptian for spying for
Mossad, the Israeli intelligence, to undermine Egypt's national
and economic interests.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, maintaining Azam's
innocence on Sunday, called for his release. Netanyahu called the
case "a most serious development in Israeli-Egyptian relations"
but he denied bilateral ties would deteriorate because of it.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is the first Arab country to sign a peace treaty with
Israel but ties have never been warm. The spy case, however, added
to the tensions in the context of the Mideast peace deadlock. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
