<HEADLINE> Tourism Boom to Continue in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- About 80 percent of the
Chinese people consider traveling fashionable, and 65 percent are
vowing to tour all over the country in their lifetime, a national
survey has shown.
</P>
<P>
The survey conducted by "China Youth Daily" indicates tourism
has very optimistic prospects, as 84.6 percent of the respondents
disagreed that travel is only for the rich, and 81.8 percent did
not believe that Chinese are less fond of traveling than
foreigners.
</P>
<P>
The survey of over 8,000 readers of the newspaper across the
country also showed that 88.6 percent of those questioned said
they know that 1997 is designated as the "Visit China" year.
</P>
<P>
They also rated as many as 330 attractions as personal
favorites. The top three destinations are Huangshan Mountain, the
city of Guilin, and the Great Wall.
</P>
<P>
The average age of those surveyed is about 26, and their
average monthly income is 575 yuan (69.37 US dollars). The highest
amount they can afford for a journey is an averaging 1,758.8
yuan (214 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The average time they can spend for a journey is
12.5 days.
</P>
<P>
They cited May as the best travel month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
