<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Oldest City Bids for World Recognition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- China is working to get its
oldest city of Chengtou -- perhaps the oldest city in the world --
included on UNESCO's world cultural heritage list.
</P>
<P>
To this end, China is to set up an archeological research
center in Lixian County of Hunan Province, where the
6,000-year-old city was built.
</P>
<P>
A meeting was held this summer to discuss how to make the
oldest city famous worldwide. Experts discussed the significance
of the site and suggested that China apply for the honor at UNESCO.
</P>
<P>
Centered around Chengtou hill, the city was first excavated in
1974. Archeologists have found completely preserved sites and
abundant relics, including well-designed houses, a moat and tombs.
</P>
<P>
They have also found a massive stretch of farmland out of the
city where eight types of rice are believed to have been planted
6,500 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Now the site is called the "Research Center for Chengtou Hill
Prehistoric Culture."
</P>
<P>
The city, together with other ancient sites discovered in the
region, has provided important clues for the origins of city,
agriculture and even the human civilization as a whole, experts
said.
</P>
<P>
The site has attracted scholars and tourists from Japan, the
Republic of Korea and the US over the past years. In 1995, Chinese
President Jiang Zemin inspected the site and inscribed a sign for
it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
