<HEADLINE> Philippines Needs Much Funds for Telecommunications </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines is estimated to
need 2 billion U.S. dollars per year until year 2000 in upgrading
its telecommunications infrastructure facilities.
</P>
<P>
A report released today by the Board of Investments said about
500,000 to 700,000 telephone lines will be installed yearly during
the same period.
</P>
<P>
"The domestic market for telecommunication products has bright
prospects for both local and foreign investments," it noted.
</P>
<P>
The telecommunications equipment manufacturing sector, one of
the major industries which has been spurring the electronics
industry, posted an average growth rate of 25.8 percent during the
past five years.
</P>
<P>
But even with the existence of a number of telephone
manufacturers, a substantial amount of telephone sets are still
being imported, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the imported telephone sets come from Hong Kong and
Japan, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Electronics and semiconductors remained the country's top
export items during the first six months of this year, with
exports amounting to 4.4 billion dollars, up 41 percent from last
year.
</P>
<P>
The industry contributes an average 36.3 percent of the
country's total exports for the past six years, the report showed.
</P>
<P>
The top five markets for Philippine electronics products are
the United States, Japan, the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations, the United Kingdom and Germany.  
</P>
</TEXT>
