<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People's Daily Editorial Stresses Water-Soil Conservation (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Today's People's Daily carried
a frontpage editorial calling for the conservation of water and
soil in the country.
</P>
<P>
The article, titled "To Re-establish the Splendor and Beauty of
Our Mountains and Rivers," says that the campaign is an important
strategic decision made by the third generation of leadership of
the Communist Party of China (CPC).
</P>
<P>
It says that prior to the convening of the 15th National
Congress of the CPC, which opens on September 12, President Jiang
Zemin and Premier Li Peng along with other Chinese leaders have
asked the nation to control soil erosion by planting trees and
establishing an ecologically-oriented agricultural program.
</P>
<P>
They want to "rebuild northwest China into a region with
beautiful mountains and rivers," the paper says. The region now
has a severe soil erosion problem.
</P>
<P>
The article notes that the work relates to the realization of
the country's socialist modernization, as the environment is
the basis for human existence and development, as well as for the
development of the economy and society.
</P>
<P>
It adds that after 40-odd years of hard work, China has planted
34.25 million hectares of trees, harnessed 700,000 square kilometers
of eroded land and 30 million hectares of desert.
</P>
<P>
The work has helped improve the environment, develop the
agricultural sector and increase farmers' income, according to the
paper.
</P>
<P>
However, it notes, some 3.6 million square kilometers of land,
or 38 percent of the country's total territory, suffer from soil
erosion, and some 2.62 million square kilometers of land, or 27.3
percent of the national territory, have been
desertified. Moreover, an additional 2,460 square kilometers of
land is desertified every year.
</P>
<P>
The paper says that it is fully possible to recapture the
beauty of the mountains and rivers in the northwest, because the
region had for a long period been prosperous and covered with
trees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People's Daily Editorial Stresses Soil Conservation (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It says that some 2,000 years ago 50 percent of the Loess
Plateau in the northwest was covered by forests, and the rest was
fertile grassland. According to historical documents, the region
had many mountains and forests in ancient times and people made
their houses out of wood.
</P>
<P>
The article says that over the past 40 years, particularly in
the past dozen years, the poor environmental conditions of some
cities and counties in the region have been tackled. This
demonstrates that with the active participation and support of the
people, there is no difficulty that cannot be overcome, all the
faces of the mountains and rivers will be changed, and poverty
wiped out.
</P>
<P>
The article says that to beautify the mountains and rivers,
people should reach a common understanding that protection of the
environmental protection means the protection of the productive
forces, and that a sound environment is the basis for the
development of the economy.
</P>
<P>
"In addition, the environment is the lifeline for agricultural
development and human existence," the article stresses.
</P>
<P>
It asks the people to concentrate on the difficult work of
harnessing the land by fully using the advantages of the socialist
system.
</P>
<P>
The CPC leadership should play the key role in the work which
will benefit future generations, it says, adding that cadres at
various levels must take the lead.
</P>
<P>
The article notes that as the work is not easy and will take
a long time, it must begin next winter and spring so
as to achieve noticeable progress soon.
</P>
<P>
"Our country's environment will have a brand new appearance
with the efforts of cadres and the people, and the target set by
CPC General Secretary Jiang Zemin will no doubt be reached," it
concludes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
