<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Premier Li Peng Supports Development of Ecology-farming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng has
asked that measurable achievements be made over the next 15 years
in harnessing soil erosion on the Loess Plateau, in a move to
bring the Yellow River under control in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
In his comments on a report by Vice-Premier Jiang Chunyun about
harnessing of soil erosion in northern Shaanxi Province and
developing of eco-agriculture, Li said the Yellow River, which
runs through the Loess Plateau, brings large amounts of silt to
its lower reaches and causes floods, a problem which has long
plagued the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
However, the river has been calm in the past 50 years since new
China was founded, as a result of comprehensive harnessing plans,
Li said.
</P>
<P>
The damming of the river for the Xiaolangdi Project offers good
opportunities for water and soil preservation on the plateau, he
said. More should be done to afforest wasteland, develop an
eco-agriculture plan, and beautify the northwest region, as
President Jiang Zemin instructed.
</P>
<P>
The Vice-Premier was asked to present a program on the
harnessing of the Loess Plateau for examination and approval of
the Party and the State Council, Li said, adding that the project
of harnessing the river course at the lower reaches and of
reinforcing dykes and dams should receive equal emphasis.
</P>
<P>
The once barren Yan'an is now covered with lush greenery, while
Yulin Prefecture, which suffered from serious desertization, now
grows rice thanks to construction of a shelterbelt and ground
water tapping. Northern Shaanxi will probably become one of the
country's most prosperous regions with a beautiful landscape, Li
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
