<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Exports Register Big Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The turnaround in the global
electronics demand has helped the Philippines improve its export
performance in the first seven months of this year with an
increase of 22 percent in export income over last year.
</P>
<P>
"Income from merchandise exports for the first seven months of
the year improved by 22 percent to 13.763 billion U.S. dollars
from 11.276 billion dollars last year," the National Statistic
Office said in a report released here today.
</P>
<P>
The office said that for July alone, export shipments posted a
21.8 percent gain as receipts reached 2.063 billion dollars,
surpassing the 1.694 billion dollars in 1996 by 369.67 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Electronics and components, accounting for 37.9 percent of the
aggregate export revenue for July 1997, remained as the top dollar
earner with receipts valued at 782.69 million dollars, or 23.3
percent higher than the year-ago level of 634.92 million dollars,"
the office said.
</P>
<P>
It said that exports of articles of apparel and clothing
accessories, cornering 11 percent of the total, inched up 2.4
percent to 227.20 million dollars in July.
</P>
<P>
Receipts from input, output and peripheral units, representing
8 percent of the total, increased 1,303.9 percent to 165.8 million
dollars from 11.81 million dollars last year, it said.
</P>
<P>
Economists here said that the devaluation of the Philippine
peso by 16 percent since July 11 and the increasing demand of
electronics in the world market could help the country improve
further its export performance this year.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Japan and Singapore are the Philippines
major trade partners.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
