<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Luxury Buses Running in Northeast China's Heilongjiang Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, September 3 (Xinhua) -- As high-grade roads are being
extended in the remote province of Heilongjiang, officials there
are on a shopping spree for luxury buses to make road travel both
quick and cushy.
</P>
<P>
On August 21, the first batch of 22 luxury coaches, each with a
price tag of two million yuan (240,960 US dollars), were put into
operation by a company affiliated with the Provincial Transportation
Department, thus unveiling a plan calling for fine-quality and fast
transport on highways.
</P>
<P>
The new buses, which run between Harbin, the provincial
capital, and Jiamusi, Hegang, and Shuangyashan, can cut the
previous travel time by two thirds, and are 50 percent faster than
the railway speed. The cost of a luxury bus ticket is equal to
that of a hard-seat train.
</P>
<P>
More such buses, which provide service likened to that on an
airplane, are expected to be put into use by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
It is also believed that by the year 2000, about 200 luxury
coaches will be in use, including some on a route linking Harbin
with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
With the opening to traffic of four new roads in August and
October, the length of quality highways in this northernmost
region of China will reach 1,666 kilometers. In the coming three
years, 3,000 kilometers more will be added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
