<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thai Baht Plunges Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Continued dollar-buying
dragged the Thai currency further down to a record low of 35.20
baht to the U.S. dollar in local spot trading on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
For the first time, the Thai currency sank below the 35 baht
level against the greenback, a 36.49 percent plunge from 25.79
baht per dollar prior to its floatation on July 2.
</P>
<P>
The baht was traded at 34.90 to 35.20 per dollar, compared with
34.55 at the close of trading on Monday. The offshore baht was
quoted at 34.28, down from 34.40.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Thailand set its reference rate for the greenback
at 34.452, up from 34.330 on Monday.
</P>
<P>
So far, no signs of central bank intervention have been
detected.
</P>
<P>
Heavy dollar-buying caused tight liquidity, forcing banks to
raise their interbank lending rates, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
The central bank has continued to absorb cash out of the market
through the repurchase window, hoping to prevent banks from
selling baht in favor of the rising dollar.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts attribute the slide to widespread fears over
ongoing political and economic uncertainties in the country.
</P>
<P>
Satian Tantanasari, senior vice president of Thai Danu Bank's
treasury department, said that the baht was hit by an extreme lack
of positive news to drive the market.
</P>
<P>
A dealer from Nakornthon Bank said investors decided to buy
dollars as they do not know what will happen in future.
</P>
<P>
Siri Ganjarerndee, assistant governor of the Bank of Thailand,
admitted that the bath's weakness reflects a deterioration in
investor confidence regarding economic and political stability.
</P>
<P>
The controversial draft of Thailand's new constitution, which
aims to put an end to patronage system and stop money politicking,
is scheduled to be debated in parliament starting Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Although public sentiment is to support the draft, the
government, which is seeking amendments to it before putting it to
vote, has not indicated it will vote for it.
</P>
<P>
If the draft is rejected by the National Assembly in the vote,
possibly before the end of the month, the draft will have to be
decided upon by a nationwide referendum, which, many people fear,
may lead to confrontation between opponents and supporters of the
draft.
</P>
<P>
There have also been other speculations such as a coup,
dissolution of the parliament, and resignation of the prime
minister, although Prime Minister Chavalit Yonchaiyudh himself has
denied all these rumors.
</P>
<P>
A dealer from Standard Chartered Bank said that the market was
driven by strong demand for the greenback as Thai corporations
continued to buy dollars to change their foreign-currency debts
into baht.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, on the stock market, after declining continually for
almost a month, the Stock Exchange of Thailand (SET) index on
Tuesday showed a rapid rise to close 21.53 points up, or 4.36
percent, to finish at 515.37 points.
</P>
<P>
While an analyst said the rise in the SET index was driven by
speculative purposes, a report in The Nation, a local newspaper,
quoted today an analyst at a local security house as saying,
"while the baht is still taking a further nose-dive, the SET index
is rising. I'm not sure which theory should be applied to explain
the situation now."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Urges Teachers To Set Moral Example for Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The State Education Commission
said here today that all Chinese teachers should set good moral
examples for their students by demonstrating their enjoyment for
the job and putting an end to corporal punishment for errant
students.
</P>
<P>
According to revised regulations on professional morality for
primary and high school teachers, the teachers must do their job
well and behave appropriately, a spokeswoman for the commission
noted.
</P>
<P>
She said that the current trend among some teachers to worship
money, seek pleasure and pursue personal interests must be
stopped, and the teachers are banned from inflicting physical
punishment of any kind on students.
</P>
<P>
In addition, they are not allowed to trade their job for
selfish purposes, and to discriminate against students, she added.
</P>
<P>
She explained that although there are already many good
teachers, the overall morale should be improved to meet the fast
development of the sector.
</P>
<P>
She revealed that educational departments and schools will
create a system to supervise the teachers' moral performance.
</P>
</TEXT>
