<HEADLINE> Indonesia Calls for International Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia sought better
cooperation among Asia-pacific states to eradicate poverty in the
region at the 27th Asia and Pacific Conference on Social Welfare
which opened here Tuesday, sources attending the conference said
today.
</P>
<P>
In an opening speech at the five-day conference attended by 300
local and foreign participants, Indonesian President Soeharto said
that some 800 million of the world's estimated 1.118 billion poor
people live in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
The president said that development would succeed only if
people were full involved in the development process.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the incredible scientific, technological and
communication advances in the world today, there is still a large
number of poor people," the president said.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto called for closer cooperation to eradicate poverty and
help people free themselves from backwardness and misery.
</P>
<P>
"Absolute poverty may create social upheaval and political
instability. The problem could only be resolved through collective
action," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Briefing on poverty eradication program in Indonesia, Soeharto
said Indonesia has been able to cut the number of poor people from
70 million in the 1960s to 26 million in 1993 and 22 million in
1996.
</P>
<P>
The conference will discuss various topics on social and
economic issues, including eradication of poverty and gap, and
social justice and economic growth, the sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
