<HEADLINE> Pak-Indian Talks Likely in Late September: Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The next round of the
foreign secretary level talks between Pakistan and India is likely
to resume some time during the second half of this month,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
The possibility of Pak-Indian foreign secretary level talks in
the month of September, as agreed by the two sides in the second
round of such talks here in June, "cannot be ruled out," the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
"At least Pakistan is ready to go into the third round of talks
even if India tries to backtrack on some key issues," they said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and India resumed their foreign secretary level talks
in March after a hiatus of three years amid signs of improved
relations between the two arch rivals in South Asia. The Talks
broke down in January 1994 due to their differences over the issue
of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
The officials, however, said that India had reportedly proposed
September 10 to 13 as tentative dates for the start of the third
round of the talks.
</P>
<P>
"But we think the talks, if going well, will take place around
September 14 or afterwards," they said.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the dialogue process between Pakistan and
India will resume after the forthcoming meeting of the prime
ministers of the two countries in New York, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and his Indian
counterpart I.K. Gujral are likely to meet on September 23 in New
York, where they will go for the U.N. General Assembly meetings on
September 22, a local news paper reported today. 
</P>
