<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Transportation Deaths Increase in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- More than 44,500 people
were killed in transportation accidents in the United States last
year, up from 44,437 the year before, said an official report
today.
</P>
<P>
The National Transportation Safety Board reported that highway
and air accidents were the main cause to the increased deaths, and
as usual the roads were the biggest killer, claiming 41,907 lives,
up from 41,798 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
National Highway Traffic Safety Administration officials
estimated that as many as one-third of the accidents and
two-thirds of the resulting fatalities could be blamed on the
increase in aggressive driving.
</P>
<P>
Aviation deaths grew from 970 to 1,089 including those in air
taxis, foreign planes that crashed in the United States and
commuter crashes.
</P>
<P>
Two major accidents -- ValuJet and TWA Flight 800 --
contributed to the jump in airline fatalities from 168 in 1995 to
380 in 1996. Private pilots accounted for 631 fatalities last
year, down from 733.
</P>
<P>
Railroad deaths totaled 740 last year, up just sightly from 736
a year earlier. Deaths on commuter and light rail climbed from 98
to 120. Deaths at railroad grade crossings fell from 579 to 472.
</P>
<P>
Marine accidents showed a decline, falling from 912 deaths in
1995 to 769 last year, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Cuts Tariffs on Oil Product Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 3 (Xinhua) -- the Thai cabinet has agreed to
cut tariffs on imported finished oil products, local newspapers
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Under the decision, the tariffs on all imported finished oil
products will be reduced to one satang (0.03 U.S. cent) per liter
from 5.5 satang (0.18 cent) per liter, a ranking Thai official was
quoted as saying on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government will raise the excise tax on some key
oil products, the official reportedly disclosed.
</P>
<P>
The excise tax on gasoline, high-speed diesel oil and kerosene
produced by local refineries reportedly will rise by 5.5 satang
per liter, while the tax on fuel oil will be up 0.5 percent based
on its current price.  
</P>
</TEXT>
