<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Work Closely with Other ASEAN Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is ready to work more
closely with other members of the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) for prosperity of the country and the region, a
senior official said.
</P>
<P>
Minister for National Planning and Economic Development
Brigadier General Abel made the remarks here Tuesday at the
opening of an Indonesian public company, the Astra Graphia Co.
Ltd., which is a subsidiary of Astra International engaged in
information technology, document services and telecommunication
systems, the official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Abel said that investment from other ASEAN countries in
Myanmar, which was just admitted into the grouping in July,
accounted for about 45 percent of the total foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN investment has helped the country obtain much-needed
foreign exchange, create jobs and achieve higher growth rates.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Ambassador to Myanmar A. Poerwanto Lenggono said
that the opening of the company adds to the group of Indonesian
companies doing business in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The Ambassador also said that Indonesia's investment, which
ranks eighth in Myanmar's foreign investment, has amounted to
236.37 million U.S. dollars in eight permitted projects in sectors
including cement and oil.
</P>
<P>
Visiting ASEAN Secretary General Ajit Singh also attended the
opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest official figures, of the 6.361 billion
U.S. dollar total foreign investment in Myanmar, five ASEAN
countries -- Singapore, Thailand, Malaysia, Indonesia and the
Philippines -- shared 3.123 billion dollars in 129 projects at the
end of July this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
