<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Military Presence Benefits S'pore Economy: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Singapore is benefiting from
the U.S. military presence here as tens of millions of dollars are
pumped into the country's economy every year by American military
units located here, a Business Times report said today.
</P>
<P>
In addition, millions more are spent by U.S. sailors when they
steam into harbor for port visits, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the money spent in restaurants, shops and
places of entertainment by American sailors granted "liberty", or
shore leave, easily amount to 1,000 to 1,500 Singapore dollars
(about 662.25 to 993.38 U.S. dollars) per sailor.
</P>
<P>
Singapore and the United States signed a Memorandum of
Understanding (MOU) in 1990, allowing the U.S. Air Force units to
come to Singapore several times each year on training deployments.
</P>
<P>
The document also permits increases in the number and duration
of visits by U.S. Navy ships.
</P>
<P>
The MOU also allows a small U.S. Navy unit, Comlog Westpac, to
use facilities provided by the Singapore government at Sembawang
in the northern part of Singapore island.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 97 U.S. Navy ships visited Singapore. And for this
year to date, there has been 90 port visits, the report said.
</P>
<P>
A senior U.S. military officer was quoted as revealing that the
two U.S. military units here have a total staff strength of about
1,000, including a small number of Singaporeans. And their
salaries total some 7.35 million Singapore dollars (about 4.87
million U.S. dollars) a year.
</P>
<P>
Besides, rent and utility payments for quarters occupied by
military personnel amount to another 10.2 million Singapore
dollars (about 6.75 million U.S. dollars) per year, the officer
said.
</P>
<P>
The officer also said that during the 1996 U.S. fiscal year,
from October 1, 1995 to September 30, 1996, the American navy
spent about 31 million Singapore dollars (about 20.53 million U.S.
dollars) in Singapore on ship supply services and repairs
performed by local yards.
</P>
<P>
This year, the U.S. Navy has already spent about 30 million
Singapore dollars (about 19.88 million U.S. dollars) on ship
supply and repair work.
</P>
<P>
Expenditures by the U.S. Air Force unit at Paya Lebar, the
497th Fighter Training Squadron for its "Commando Sling"
exercises, amounted to 5.1 million Singapore dollars (about 3.38
million U.S. dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
In addition, another 7.2 million Singapore dollars (about 4.77
million U.S. dollars) are pumped into the Singapore economy yearly
through airplane fuel contracts, the report quoted the officer as
saying.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
