<HEADLINE> Pakistani, Indian PMs to Meet in New York: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif and his Indian counterpart I.K. Gujral are likely to
meet in New York on September 23, a local newspaper reported
today.
</P>
<P>
This will be the first meeting between the two outside South
Asia.
</P>
<P>
"The date and time of the premiers' meeting has not been
officially finalized as yet, but given the visit schedule of the
two leaders they are likely to meet on September 23," The News
quoted a senior official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Though both the leaders are unlikely to spring any major
surprise, the official said, the talks will be productive and its
outcome might lead to some positive developments in addressing
some crucial issues between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"The two leaders will pick up the thread where they left in
Male," the official said, referring to Nawaz and Gujral's meeting
in May in the Maldive capital during which the two agreed to
improve the strained relations between Pakistan and India.
</P>
<P>
It was after quite a few contradictory statements that Gujral
finally evinced his "keen interest" Monday to have talks with
Sharif in New York.
</P>
<P>
Both prime ministers are supposed to meet U.S. President Bill
Clinton separately as they go to New York for the U. N. General
Assembly meetings on September 22.  
</P>
</TEXT>
