<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast Company Reports Major Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Jihua Group, which is based in
northeast China's Jilin Province, reported 231.25 million yuan
(28.2 million US dollars) in economic losses in the first half of
the year, "China Securities News" reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, the group has issued 1.8 billion
yuan in corporate bonds since 1996, and it is the first time a
corporate bond issuer declared such a huge loss.
</P>
<P>
The group, a parent company with a 70 percent stake in Hong
Kong-listed Jilin Chemical Fiber Co. Ltd., attributed the losses
to depreciation of facilities, rising costs, price hikes in
crude oil, and a price fall for its products.
</P>
<P>
The group issued 800 million yuan of corporate bonds, with an
annual interest rate of 15 percent, on Shanghai Securities
Exchange in January, 1996, and another one billion yuan worth of
bonds, with an annual interest rate of 11 percent, last
February. The second batch of bonds issue will soon be traded on
the Shanghai bourse.
</P>
<P>
Jilin Chemical Fiber Co. Ltd, listed both in Hong Kong and
Shenzhen, also reported a 62.77-percent drop in profits during the
first six months of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
