<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Neolithic Wares Unearthed in Southern Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A team of Italian speleologists
recently excavated two well-preserved pottery pots and other wares
of the Neolithic age dating back to 3,000 years ago in Salve,
south Italy's Lecce Province.
</P>
<P>
Press reports today quoted archeologists with Rome's second
university as saying that these wares, discovered in a cave, might
have been used in religious rituals for worshiping the god.
</P>
<P>
The finding is of great significance because it proves the
existence of herdsmen and animal raisers in the region during the
Neolithic age, the archeologists were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Before the latest discovery, some prehistoric relics had been
found in the same cave. In the 1970s, a number of ancient murals
were discovered in it.
</P>
<P>
Now, the cave has been close down to preserve other historical
relics that possibly exist. Speleologists will further explore the
cave for more findings, according reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Troops in Bosnia Get New Grenades Against Serbs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The United States has armed
its troops in Bosnia with "non-lethal" hand grenades to control
crowds of angry Serbs and mark them with dye, the Pentagon said
today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking during a regular briefing, Pentagon spokesman Ken
Bacon said that the 40-mm sponge grenades, which are designed to
knock people down in crowds when hit in the chest or the abdomen
at a range of 15 to 30 meters were sent to the soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the U.S. troops will also be armed with some
dye-marking kits, which look like hand grenades filled with dye
that can be thrown at people in crowds so that they are marked
with this dye and can be found and punished later.
</P>
<P>
"Those are two non-lethal pieces of equipment that are in the
process of being issued," the spokesman said. "They were...
shipped into the theater over the weekend, and training teams
arrived yesterday and will begin training troops in Bosnia... to
use this equipment."
</P>
<P>
Bacon warned that the non-lethal weaponry would be for
"supplemental" use and would not prevent U.S. troops from using
their M-16 rifles or other lethal weapons if necessary.
</P>
<P>
Bacon also confirmed reports that U.N. and the NATO-led
Stabilization Force (SFOR) officials had reached agreement with
Pale-backed Serb Radio and Television to stop "inflammatory"
reports.
</P>
<P>
He said the agreement signed by Serb Radio and Television
Editor-in-Chief Drago Vukovic on Tuesday has not only promised to
halt inflammatory broadcasts undermining the Dayton accords but
also to give time to broadcast "other political views."
</P>
<P>
"This is designed to prevent the Serb media against inaccurate,
rhetorical flourishes against the Dayton peace process as they
have been doing in using the media to stir up the population
against the Dayton peace process," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
