<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Doctors Urge Refrain From Antibiotics Over-use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Thai doctors have called for
rational use of antibiotic drugs to prevent bio-resistance to the
drugs, local newspaper "The Nation" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Sayomporn Sirinavin, from the Ramathibodi Hospital, voiced
concern over the irrational use of antibiotic drugs in Thailand,
saying that it can lead to an epidemic of drug resistance in the
same way as aids.
</P>
<P>
She expressed her worries in the wake of recent reports that at
least one case of vancomycin resistance has occurred in the united
states. Vancomycin is the latest derivative of antibiotics, which
have broad effects on bacteria.
</P>
<P>
Sayomporn said on Tuesday at a panel discussion that for
vancomycin resistance, there is no drug to cure it now, just like
aids.
</P>
<P>
Citing the principles of science, she said if drug resistance
breaks out anywhere in the world, it can occur in other places and
actually lead to further over-use of drugs.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Anuwat Suphachutikul, director of research projects of the
Health Systems Research Institute, also urged doctors, pharmacists
and patients to be aware of the over-use of antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
He said antibiotic drugs represent as much as one-fourth of the
total expenditure on drugs.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Pramual Sunakorn, a former director of the Children's
Health Institute, pointed to research which showed that only seven
percent of doctors prescribe antibiotics in a responsible manner.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
