<HEADLINE> Leaders Agree to Create Central American Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Central American leaders
agreed today to start working toward the establishment of a
political and economic union in the region following the end of
the 20th annual regional summit.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rican Foreign Minister Fernando Naranjo said the idea was
to gradually create a union similar to that formed by European
countries.
</P>
<P>
The presidents from Costa Rica, Guatemala, Honduras, Nicaragua,
Panama and El Salvador and the prime minister of Belize agreed at
the one-day summit to establish a high-level commission to work
out the conditions for the formation of the union.
</P>
<P>
The leaders urged people in the region to give their full
support to the project in order to create a "common house" for
Central Americans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
