<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Opens Service Sector Wider to Outside World (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Now, 37 retail joint ventures have been formed, eight of which
are operational. Furthermore, a pilot project has begun on
establishing Sino-foreign chain stores.
</P>
<P>
Other areas of the service sector that are accessible to
overseas investment include air transport, general aviation, goods
supply and selling, foreign trade, securities, accounting,
auditing, and legal consultancy, according to a 1995 directory for
overseas investment in China.
</P>
<P>
In January, China approved the first overseas-backed business
in the field of aviation fuels, while in July, the first
Sino-overseas foreign trade company opened in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
And more recently, a railway jointly funded by inland and Hong
Kong investors, was open to traffic. The law on highways, adopted
in July, stipulates that road building is open to overseas
participation.
</P>
<P>
The service sector has entered a period of fast development
since the reform and opening up drive which began in the early
1980s. Statistics show that contributions to GDP by the sector
have risen from 23.7 percent in 1978 to 32.3 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
However, this still lags far behind the 70 percent produced by
developed countries, an economist said, but added that China also
has great potential to develop the sector.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Premier Li Lanqing pointed out that China will gradually
promote the opening up of the service trades.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
