<HEADLINE> Tuna Producers to Boycott U.S. Tuna Embargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Tuna-producing countries are
trying to issue a multinational agreement to block further
protectionist initiatives disguised behind "ecologic masks."
</P>
<P>
Fishery officials from Colombia, Costa Rica, Ecuador, Mexico
and Venezuela will meet on September 14 and 15 in Ensenada, a port
city in northern Mexico, to prepare the document.
</P>
<P>
The objective of the meeting is to ensure the document defends
the interests of Latin American countries, prior to the Forum of
the Inter-Governmental Commission for Tropical Tuna, scheduled for
September 29 in the U.S. port city of La Jolla.
</P>
<P>
The Latin American countries fishing yellow-finned tuna in the
east Pacific were affected by a U.S. embargo under the alleged
fact that tuna fishing with methods used by Latin American boats
caused dolphins to get hooked in their nets. 
</P>
