<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investment Funds in China on Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- China's stable economic growth
is paving the way for the development of investment funds, "China
Daily" today quoted a senior bank official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Yin Jieyan, Vice-Governor of the People's Bank of China, said
China successfully achieved a "soft landing" last year, marked by
reined-in inflation and sustained economic growth. Yin made the
remarks while briefing participants to a symposium on operational
issues of investment funds.
</P>
<P>
Yin said investment funds, with a stress on increasing capital,
professional management and long-term earning, have become one of
the four pillars of the global financial industry together with
stocks, bonds and futures.
</P>
<P>
Compared with many other countries, China's securities
investment funds are still in a rudimentary stage of development,
said Yin.
</P>
<P>
Over the past six years, the number of investment funds in
China has grown from zero to 75, with a market value of 5.8
billion yuan (700 million US dollars). Among them, 25 funds are
being traded in the Shanghai and Shenzhen stock exchanges.
</P>
<P>
There are some 40 fund managing firms around the country.
</P>
<P>
The official said China would learn skills and lessons from
overseas fund managers and develop its own investment funds
suitable for China's conditions.
</P>
<P>
Information from the symposium also disclosed that China has
been considering establishing joint venture funds which would be
allowed to trade domestic shares. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
