<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Rupiah, Shares Weaken Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Despite the restrictions on
forward foreign exchange transactions, the Indonesian rupiah
weakened further against the U.S. dollar Tuesday to cross the
3,000 level and stock prices also fell by 1.4 percent, dealers and
brokers said today.
</P>
<P>
Foreign exchange dealers said the ceiling on forward selling to
non-resident at 5 million U.S. dollars per customer could not
salvage the rupiah as domestic appetite for the dollar remained
high.
</P>
<P>
Spot rupiah, which opened at 3,010/3,030 Tuesday, continued to
weaken to close at 3,040/3,060.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, share prices on the Jakarta Stock Exchange fell 1.4
percent on continued uncertainty over when the government would
ease rupiah liquidity and cut down interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The Jakarta Stock Exchange Index closed down 6.955 points at
479.014, with total turnover of 205.2 million shares valued at 93
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Stock analysts attributed the continuing doldrums in the stock
market to the rupiah volatility and regional stock market's
bearish trend.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's rupiah, like other regional currencies, has come
under fierce speculative attacks following de factor devaluation
of the Thai baht and the Philippine pose in July.
</P>
<P>
Despite many measures have been taken by the Indonesian
government, the value of rupiah has dropped by about 25 percent
since early this year. Last Friday the rupiah fell to a historic
low of 3,070 against the U.S. dollar.  
</P>
</TEXT>
