<HEADLINE> Closer Cooperation Helps Construction in HK, Interior of China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese construction
official is calling for closer cooperation between the
construction companies in the interior of China and their Hong
Kong counterparts to bring the former into line with
international practices.
</P>
<P>
"The co-operation is sure to help the whole country, including
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region, to attain a much
bigger share in the international construction market," Nian Fuli,
Vice-Director of the Construction Industry Department of the
Ministry of Construction (MOC), was quoted by today's "China
Daily" as saying.
</P>
<P>
Nian made the remarks yesterday during a symposium on
construction procurement and contract administration in China
held in the Hong Kong Polytechnic University, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
"We have much to learn from Hong Kong's construction industry,
which boasts advanced technology and administration methods," said
Nian.
</P>
<P>
Nian, who led a group of 14 provincial government officials
responsible for the construction industry, said the symposium, the
second since last year, aims to improve the relationship between
the construction industries in the interor of China and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
China's construction industry is expected to grow at a rate two
to three percent higher than the country's national economy during
the next ten years, Nian said.
</P>
<P>
By 2010, China's floor space of newly built urban and rural
houses will top 12.5 billion sq m, with a total investment of
6,000 billion yuan (722 billion US dollars), Nian said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics suggest 11 Hong Kong companies won bids for 49 large
projects in Shanghai already this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
