<HEADLINE> Seles Ousted, Chang Continues at U.S. Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Monica Seles of the United
states was upset by unfavorited Irina Spirlea of Romania while her
compatriot Michael Chang advanced to the semi-finals by beating
Cedric Pioline of France at the US Open tennis here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Second-seeded Seles squandered a match point against Irina
Spirlea before the 11th-seeded Romanian came back to win 6-7(5/7),
7-6(10/8), 6-3 to reach the first Grand Slam semi-final of her
career.
</P>
<P>
Chang, the second seed who inherited the mantle of US Open
favorite in the wake of Pete Sampras' shocking defeat on Monday,
made a tremendous rally to overcome Pioline 6-3, 0-6, 5-7, 7-5,
6-1.
</P>
<P>
Chang trailed 2-5 in the fourth set, but won 11 of the last 12
games to take the match that lasted three hours and 41 minutes
avoiding the same upset fate as Sampras and Seles.
</P>
<P>
Chang advanced to a quarter-final against the next-highest
seeded player left in the draw, No. 10 Marcelo Rios of Chile, who
gained the spot by eliminating seventh seed Sergi Bruguera of
Spain.
</P>
<P>
Unseeded Swede Magnus Larsson beat South African Wayne Ferreira
6-3, 7-6 (7/5), 6-3 and awaited the winner of the night match
between Andre Agassi and 13th seed Pat Rafter of Australia.
</P>
<P>
Another flamboyant American, 17-year-old Venus Williams, took
on France's Sandrine Testud for a chance to face Spirlea in the
semi-finals. 
</P>
