<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Central Bank to Reduce Liquidity Reserves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Central Bank is
expected to reduce the required liquidity reserves of banks by one
or two percentage points today to ease the liquidity crunch in the
financial system.
</P>
<P>
The Monetary Board, the policy-making body of the central bank,
was reportedly reviewing its policy on liquidity reserves as the
peso tumbled to an all-time low of 30.90 pesos to a dollar
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The review was prompted by the Bankers Association of the
Philippines which asked monetary authorities Tuesday to back down
on a recent decision to tighten the money supply, local newspaper
Manila Bulletin reported today.
</P>
<P>
Bankers said the decision had failed to protect the peso and
had pushed interest rates higher, urging the central bank to
readjust the liquidity reserves, which was increased to 8 percent
from 5 percent last week.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a ranking central bank official told another leading
newspaper Business World that last week's decision to raise the
required liquidity reserves was "only a temporary measure" meant
to siphon off excess peso funds in the system.
</P>
<P>
By increasing the liquidity reserves, the central bank was able
to siphon off some 30.9 billion pesos (1 billion U.S. dollars)
from the system, which effectively limited the opportunity of
banks to buy dollars with their peso funds.
</P>
<P>
However, this move backfired as Treasury bill (T-bill) interest
rates shot up to five-year highs on Monday and interbank loan
rates soared to a high of 75 percent on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The reduction in the reserves requirement is expected to free
additional funds into the system, thus, allow banks to quote lower
rates at the T-bill auction, the official said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
