<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Opens Service Sector Wider to Outside World (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- China is opening up its
service sector wider to the outside world, with almost no area in
the industry excluded from overseas investment, said an official
with the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Experiments are being carried out to open the industries of
banking, insurance, communications, tourism, commerce,
consultancy, services, which in the past have been inaccessible to
foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
By now, financial institutions from more than 40 countries and
regions have opened 540 representative offices in China, 162 of
which are already in operation, with nine permitted to deal in
Chinese Renminbi yuan. Accordingly, overseas-funded financial
institutions have begun to play an important role in China's
banking system.
</P>
<P>
Insurance companies followed suit: Statistics show that 84
insurance companies from 13 countries have set up 144 offices,
four of which have been approved to conduct business in China.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, 14 overseas accounting firms have also established 28
offices in China's big cities such as Beijing and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The central government defined the speeding up of the service
sector as a strategy to improve industrial structure. In 1992, the
State Council began to intensify efforts to open the sector
gradually and comprehensively to the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
In the same year, the State Council agreed to set up one or two
Sino-overseas retail businesses in six cities including Beijing
and Shanghai, as well as in China's five special economic zones
such as Shenzhen. It was a start in the opening of the commercial
sector.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
