<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protecting China's Ancient Bamboo Slips, Wooden Tablets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Protecting and cataloguing
the bamboo slips and wooden tablets recovered from an ancient well
in Changsha, capital of south China's Hunan province, is now under
way.
</P>
<P>
Early in the morning of October 17 last year, archaeologists
found more than 170,000 bamboo slips and wooden tablets in the
well in downtown Changsha.
</P>
<P>
These are regarded as the greatest archaeological discovery
in this century in China and are believed to be archives of the local
government from 232 A.D. to 237 A.D.
</P>
<P>
According to the Municipal Bureau of Cultural Relics, earlier
this year, hundreds of bamboo slips and wooden tablets dating from
25 A.D. to 220 A.D. were discovered in another old well nearby.
</P>
<P>
The bureau said that they are being bathed in distilled water
and kept at a constant temperature.
</P>
<P>
The bureau director showed a piece of dehydrated wooden
tablet to a Xinhua reporter. It measures three centimeters by 30
centimeters and the characters on it are still clearly
visible.
</P>
<P>
"With complete and detailed records of the political, economic,
military, cultural and administrative affairs of their time, these
slips and tablets have a great historical and cultural value",
said, noting that the work will take ten or more years.
</P>
<P>
"Later when the museum for bamboo slips and wooden tablets is
completed and our research findings are published, Changsha will
be more attractive to visitors for its rich cultural relics," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the municipal government of Changsha decided to
allocate five hectares of urban land and five million yuan (some
600,000 US dollars) to support the slip and tablet project.
</P>
<P>
However, a lack of funds is still the main problem hindering
better protection. "We are looking for more financial aid from
all channels," Yang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela: No U.N. Forces Deployment on Border with Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela opposed the presence
of U.N. peacekeeping forces on the border between Venezuela and
Colombia to halt attacks by Colombian guerrillas, Venezuelan
Foreign Minister Miguel Angel Burelli Rivas said today.
</P>
<P>
The deployment of U.N. peacekeeping forces on the border would
make a local dispute internationalized and also mean the
Venezuelan troops are not capable of settling the regional
affairs, Rivas said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
It "could bring serious consequences," he said, rather than
prevent Colombian rebels from entering the Venezuelan territory.
</P>
<P>
"We can not enter the Colombian territory, but if Colombian
guerrillas raid into our territory to spread war, we will take
necessary actions," Burelli asserted.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations on the border issue between the two countries have
made some progress, but "it is still too early to announce a
definitive conclusion," added the foreign minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
