<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0130 GMT, September 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. Navy said Tuesday that it planned to
deploy a new generation of long-range Tomahawk cruise missiles
that could circle over a battlefield for hours before being
programmed to hit moving targets.
</P>
<P>
The upgrade, Navy officials told reporters, would let
ship-board commanders redirect missiles against tactical targets
such as armor columns, troop formations and mobile missile
launchers using satellite data, images from an onboard digital
camera and "real-time" updates from special forces or other
sources.
</P>
<P>
The officials said at a news conference that the updated
version would cost less than half the current model and the 1991
Gulf War. The new Tactical Tomahawk model would be able to
"loiter" over a battlefield for at least two hours while awaiting
instructions to strike, the Navy said.
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- The U.S. dollar rose against major currencies
Tuesday, setting a nearly two-week high versus the German mark,
following the U.S. stock market rebound and the decision of the
German central bank to leave interest rates alone.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average made its biggest one-day point
gain ever. Frantic buying of stocks increased demand for dollars.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also got some help from a weak Japanese retail sales
report that added to the pessimism about Japan's economy. Japan's
minister of finance suggested interest rates will remain low and
said the yen's recent weakness is in line with economic
fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 1.8335
German marks, up from 1.8095 late Friday. U.S. financial markets
were closed Monday for Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The Buckingham Palace has called on the British
people to observe a one-minute national silence for Princess Diana
at the funeral due to be held at London's Westminster Abbey
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Responding to the overwhelming affection for Princess Diana,
who was killed in a tragic Paris car crash last Sunday, the
Buckingham Palace has also decided to establish an official
memorial fund to take donations for charities associations.
</P>
<P>
After Saturday's funeral, Diana will be buried alongside her
father at her Spencer family's ancestral estate in Althorp,
central England.
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The U.N. inquiry team in the Democratic
Republic of the Congo could start its delayed investigations on
the alleged massacres of Rwandan Hutu refugees as the country had
dropped its objections, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The foreign minister of the Democratic Republic of the Congo,
Bizima Karaha, informed U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan by phone
on Monday that the U.N. human rights investigative team in the
Congo can begin its work," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
"The objections raised in a letter to the secretary-general
signed by two ministers of the government have been dropped,"
added the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the United Nations was awaiting written
confirmation of this and the investigation team was making
preparation to start its work.
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- Despite the discovery that the chauffeur of the late
Princess of Wales was drunk when death descended on her Saturday
night, the French judicial authorities Tuesday did not let go the
six photographers and one motorcyclist who were caught pursuing
her.
</P>
<P>
They were charged by the Paris Public Prosecutor for
"involuntary homicide and injury" and "non assistance to person in
danger."
</P>
<P>
The photographers are Nicolas Arsov of the Sipa agency, Jacques
Langevin of the Sygma agency, Laslo Veres, an independent
photographer, Serge Arnal of the Stills agency, Romulad Rat of the
Gamma agency and Christian Martinez of the Angeli agency. The
motorcyclist is Stephane Darmon of the Gamma agency.
</P>
<P>
Six of them were released in the evening but were put under
judicial control after being questioned by Judge Herve Stephan of
the Paris Investigation Court. They could face up to five years
in jail and 500,000 francs (83,400 U.S. dollars) of fines if
convicted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
