<HEADLINE> European Groups Win Water Diversion Project Bids in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Two European groups have won
bids on a water diversion project in north China's Shanxi province.
</P>
<P>
MASJV, a joint venture of Mayreder and Alpine corporations of
Austria and Shanghai Tunnel Engineering Corporation (STEC) of
China, has won a bid on three tunnels and two underground pumping
stations.
</P>
<P>
The other group, WANLONGJV, consisting of Imtpregillo and CMC
of Italy, and a Chinese hydro-electric power engineering bureau,
has won two bids on four tunnels, one aqueduct, two hidden
culverts, a flood-control gate, and a 460-meter canal.
</P>
<P>
The Wanjiazhai diversion project will divert water from the
Yellow River, China's second longest, to water-deficient Shanxi.
</P>
<P>
The project will cost 20 billion yuan (2.41 billion
U.S. dollars), of which 400 million US dollars will come from
World Bank loans.
</P>
<P>
The first phase will divert water to Taiyuan, the provincial
capital, and the second phase to Shuozhou and Datong, two major
cities in northern Shanxi. It is expected to be completed in
2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
