<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing-Kowloon Railway Boosting Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Two Chinese economists said
Tuesday they believe the year-old Beijing-Kowloon Railway has
started to affect the economy in areas alongside it by improving
the investment climate and contacts with coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
Cheng Xiusheng and Yu Bing of the State Council Development
Research Center, speaking at a seminar on development along the
Beijing-Kowloon Railway, said that the better transportation
helps turn natural and human resources into profits.
</P>
<P>
Areas along the railway produce 14 percent of the nation's
grain and 15 percent of its cotton, and are rich in mineral
resources. Their coal reserves amount to 60 billion tons. The
population density of the area is three times the national average.
</P>
<P>
The 2,381-km railway is also helping form new industrial and
commercial centers and helping old cities. It has carried 2
million tons of cargo and 47 million passengers in the past year.
</P>
<P>
Average GDP increase in the seven provinces and two
municipalities along the railway was 11.6 percent in 1996,
compared to the national average of 8.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Cui Zhongfu, an official of the State Economic and Trade
Commission, said the Beijing-Kowloon railway artery will be much
more efficient when it is linked with other railways and its
management is improved.
</P>
<P>
Only 20 percent of the railway's cargo capacity and 30 percent
of its passenger capacity were utilized in the first half of the
year.
</P>
<P>
The seminar deals with the railway's role in macro-economic
development, infrastructure construction, resource preservation,
environmental protection and investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIFA Confirms Hosts of Future World Cups </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 2 (Xinhua) -- FIFA Secretary General Joseph
S. Blatter disclosed Tuesday that the world soccer governing body
has chosen the hosts of several future world cups events but has
yet to decide on their financial sponsors.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from a three-and-half-hour meeting of the FIFA
Executive Committee that ended here Tuesday afternoon, Blatter
told reporters that the committee agreed that cannabis should be
included among banned substances.
</P>
<P>
The meeting under the chairmanship of the FIFA President Joao
Havelange was held on the eve of the Under-17 World Cup soccer
tournament, planned for Egypt on September 4-21.
</P>
<P>
"It was confirmed that the 1999 FIFA World Youth Championship
would be held in Nigeria and two years later in Argentina, while
New Zealand and Trinidad and Tobago were appointed to host the
Under-17 World Championship in 1999 and 2001, " Blatter said.
</P>
<P>
Finland had already announced its candidature for the U-17 in
2003, according to Blatter.
</P>
<P>
The final project for a first Club World Championship, to be
played in 1999, is to be discussed in further details before the
next Executive Committee meeting in December, he added.
</P>
<P>
The FIFA official said that the Executive Committee will
confirm the granting of the marketing rights for the FIFA World
Cup in 2002 and 2006 at its meeting in Marseilles on December 3.
</P>
<P>
He said that the committee has agreed in principle to renew the
contract with FIFA's current marketing partner, ISL, and with its
official equipment supplier, Adidas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
