<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Investment Zone to Emerge in Southeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 2 (Xinhua) -- China has made a big step in
getting more overseas funds for the Xiamen Special Economic Zone
(SEZ), one of five in the country, in Fujian province, by setting
up the Haicang Investment Zone.
</P>
<P>
The 100-sq.km. zone is 870 m from Xiamen and will be connected
with the SEZ by bridge to be completed by 1999.
</P>
<P>
In 1989, the Chinese government approved the investment zone,
because of the Xiamen SEZ's limited space. Since then, great
effort has been made to build roads, water and power supplies,
telecommunications, and ports.
</P>
<P>
According to Deputy Mayor Liu Chengye, Haicang will be part of
Xiamen and a key development area. A new Xiamen Port area, a new
industrial block and an urban district will be built there.
</P>
<P>
The city government hopes to speed up the development by making
good use of Xiamen's existing infrastructure, services, and
personnel, because of its rapid development in the past 15 years.
</P>
<P>
Haicang zone has a 13 km coastline, with a large bay where 49
berths, each with a handling capacity of 10,000 tons, are
planned. Annual handling capacity will reach 90 million tons when
completed.
</P>
<P>
This is expected to make Xiamen an international port
city. Haicang zone has convenient highway and railway links with
inland areas, and is an ideal place for modern industries.
</P>
<P>
It has attracted investors from Taiwan, Hong Kong, and
elsewhere, and 85 overseas-funded projects have been set up there,
with a total investment of 1.52 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
There are also 110 domestically-financed projects approved for
the zone, with total capital of 2.77 billion yuan, 27 of which are
operational and are expected to generate an output value of five
billion yuan this year.
</P>
<P>
Xiamen is one of two ports with direct shipments across the
Taiwan Straits and Haicang's first berths have been put to use. The
new investment zone is expected to play an important role in trade
and economic exchanges across the strait.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
