<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Discovers Gas Reserves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia has discovered
proved and probable natural gas reserves in excess of 13 trillion
cubic feet (TCF) in its eastern part, it was announced today.
</P>
<P>
ARCO, or Atlantic Richfield Corp., said in a press release from
Los Angeles, California, that it ranks among the largest natural
gas discoveries in the world in recent years.
</P>
<P>
On an oil equivalent basis, 13 TCF of gas equates to almost
2.2 billion barrels of oil, said ARCO which made the discovery.
</P>
<P>
The reserves are located on the Weriagar and Berau blocks
onshore and offshore Irian Jaya and development plans call for LNG
production to begin in time for anticipated increases in market
demand around 2003.
</P>
<P>
The project named Tangguh is expected to make Indonesia the
largest LNG marketer in the world with a 50 percent market share
in the Asia-Pacific region, ARCO said.
</P>
<P>
The project would add a third source to Indonesia's two
existing LNG production centers in Arun and Bontang.
</P>
<P>
ARCO investment in Indonesia has totaled nearly 3 billion U.S.
dollars, while the Tangguh project is expected to require several
billion dollars of investment, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
