<HEADLINE> US Dollar Gets Higher as Stocks Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar rose against
major currencies today, setting a nearly two-week high versus the
German mark, following the U.S. stock market rebound and the
decision of the German central bank to leave interest rates alone.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average made its biggest one-day point
gain ever. Frantic buying of stocks increased demand for dollars.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also got some help from a weak Japanese retail sales
report that added to the pessimism about Japan's economy. Japan's
minister of finance suggested interest rates will remain low and
said the yen's recent weakness is in line with economic
fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 1.8335
German marks, up from 1.8095 late Friday. U.S. financial markets
were closed Monday for Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also traded at 121.47 Japanese yen, up from 120.80.
The British pound was quoted at 1.5920 U.S. dollars, down from
1.6200 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The dollar's current level above 120 yen hadn't been seen since
early May.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday:
1.5070 Swiss francs, up from 1.4925; 6.1665 French francs, up from
6.0920; 1,786.00 Italian lire, up from 1,770.00; and 1.3841
Canadian dollars, down from 1.3883. 
</P>
</TEXT>
