<HEADLINE> US Military May Test Firing Laser at Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Defense Department
was considering an Army request to test fire laser weapon at a
satellite circling Earth, the Pentagon said today.
</P>
<P>
But no decision had been made on whether a powerful laser at
White Sands Missile Range in New Mexico would be fired at an Air
Force satellite, said Pentagon spokesman, U.S. Air Force Lt. Col.
Bob Potter.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by The New York Times Monday, the Army's
Space and Defense Command had asked for testing in September the
ability of the big laser to possibly destroy satellites or other
space vehicles in time of war.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said arms control advocates worried that it would
likely set off a race for better space weapons.
</P>
<P>
The United States has not demonstrated the ability to destroy
satellites, but defense analysts have warned that any decision by
Washington to develop an anti-satellite weapon could have major
political as well as military ramifications.
</P>
<P>
The Army has fired the laser, called Miracl (Mid-infrared
Advance Chemical Laser) at ground targets and speeding drones and
rockets in flight. It was banned from firing at satellites until
1995, when the Republican-controlled Congress let the ban expire.
</P>
<P>
Miracl produces a two-meter wide beam of light of millions of
watts by burning fuels and then extracting the energy with
mirrors. The resulting laser destroys targets with intense heat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
