<DOCNO> XIE19970903.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Researchers Link Stomach Cancer to Smoking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Over 40 percent of stomach
and esophageal cancer cases could have been caused by smoking,
according to the latest edition of the Journal of the National
Cancer Institute.
</P>
<P>
The journal said that the risk of adenocarcinoma was doubled
among current and ex-smokers and that the risk could last for even
30 years after quitting smoking.
</P>
<P>
The research was conducted by Marlie Gammon and his group at
the Columbia University School of Public Health. They studied more
than 1,000 people aged 30 to 79 who had been diagnosed with the
esophagus or stomach cancer and compared them to 600 people who
did not have cancer.
</P>
<P>
Smoking was a clear risk factors for two different kinds of
cancer: adenocarcinoma and squamous cell cancer, the researchers
said.
</P>
<P>
They found that smoking increased the risk of squamous cell
carcinoma more than five-fold and ex-smokers had a risk of nearly
three times higher of squamous cell cancer of the stomach or
esophagus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
