<HEADLINE> Sudanese, Zambian Presidents Talk Over Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Sudanese President
Omar Bashir held talks here today with his Zambian counterpart
Frederick Chiluba on the peace talks process of Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Bashir said his government is working to implement a federal
system government following calls from some quarters that the
system of government should change.
</P>
<P>
He said that the call for a federal government has become
prominent after the 1989 conference held to discuss the root
cause of the problems in his country.
</P>
<P>
The uneven distribution of wealth which lead to
under-development in many areas of the country is also identified
as one of the causes of the protracted civil war in Sudan, said
the Sudanese leader.
</P>
<P>
He assured Chiluba that his government is committed to finding
a lasting peace solution to the war so that resources can go to
the development of the country.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that relations Zambia and Sudan will be
strengthened.
</P>
<P>
In the talks, Chiluba said Zambia will play a leading role in
the peace talks, adding that Zambia should be furnished adequate
information about the conflict in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Chiluba said Sudan must come to the negotiating table
to find a peaceful solution.
</P>
<P>
Bashir arrived here today for a two-day visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
