<HEADLINE> Dow Up More Than 250 Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial
average surged more than 250 points today, a record rise, as new
data eased fears of investors for inflation pressure.
</P>
<P>
The Dow, which tumbled 265 points last week, recovered almost
all of that lost ground with a gain of 257.36 points to 7,879.78.
</P>
<P>
The 3.4 percent advance was the Dow's biggest one-day
percentage gain since a 4.6 percent gain in early 1991.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a nearly 3-to-1
margin on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 491.82
million shares as against 407.00 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 28.11 to 927.58, the
NYSE composite index rose 12.42 to 482.90, and the Nasdaq
composite index rose 30.77 to 1,618.09.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 4.62 to
428.05, its fourth consecutive record close and seventh straight
winning session. The American Stock Exchange composite index,
which is dominated by smaller companies, rose 6.71 to 656.87 for
its first record close since August 6.
</P>
<P>
Stocks stumbled last month on fears the economy was
overheating. But a report today of an unexpected slowing in the
growth rate of the nation's manufacturing economy in August helped
ease those fears. 
</P>
</TEXT>
